{"title_page": "Charlotte Figi", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Charlotte Figi\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|2006|10|18}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2020|04|07|2006|10|18}} \n| death_place   = [[Colorado Springs]], [[U.S.]]\n| nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n{{short description|American medical cannabidiol patient}}\n'''Charlotte Figi''' (October 18, 2006 \u2013 April 7, 2020) was an American girl with [[Dravet syndrome]] who took [[cannabidiol]] (CBD) oil to prevent seizures and inspired the name of the medical cannabis strain called [[Charlotte's web (cannabis)|Charlotte's Web]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/charlotte-figi-girl-severe-seizures-inspired-cbd-treatments-dies-13-n1179396|title=Charlotte Figi, girl with severe seizures that inspired CBD treatments, dies at 13|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n\nFigi was born on October 18, 2006, with a twin sister, to parents Paige and Matt Figi.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Saundra |title=Marijuana stops child's severe seizures |url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/08/07/health/charlotte-child-medical-marijuana/index.html |publisher=CNN |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=August 7, 2013}}</ref> At 3 months old, she had her first seizure.<ref name=\":5\" /> Due to her Dravet syndrome, at age five, she used a wheelchair, had up to 300 [[grand mal seizures]] a week, and had trouble speaking.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last1=Slevin |first1=Colleen |title=Girl Who Inspired Charlotte's Web Marijuana Oil Dies |url=https://apnews.com/f19a91d58ab50fad1ca2267f53ae3696 |publisher=The Associated Press |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, Figi's mother searched for CBD marijuana oil for her daughter's treatment.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |last1=Philipps |first1=Dave |title=Bid to Expand Medical Marijuana Business Faces Federal Hurdles |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/24/us/bid-to-expand-medical-marijuana-business-faces-federal-hurdles.html?searchResultPosition=3 |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |date=August 23, 2014}}</ref> Figi began taking oil from the marijuana plant, \"Hippie\u2019s Disappointment,\" which contained low THC<ref name=\":3\" /> and was later renamed Charlotte's Web.<ref name=\":2\" /> With the use of Charlotte's Web, Figi experienced an immediate reduction in her epileptic seizures, down from 300 a week to two or three per month.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web |last1=Osborne |first1=Hannah |title=Charlotte Figi: The Girl Who is Changing Medical Marijuana Laws Across America |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/charlotte-figi-girl-who-changing-medical-marijuana-laws-across-america-1453547 |publisher=International Business Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> While the use of medical marijuana was still illegal in many states, news of Figi\u2019s success spread and families with similar diagnoses started moving to Colorado Springs, where the drug was originally sold.<ref>{{cite web |title=Moving for marijuana: Families with seizure-stricken kids relocating to Colorado for strain of pot |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/health/kids-seizure-charlotte-web-pot-treatment-article-1.1619066 |publisher=New York Daily News |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=February 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Colorado Girl Who Inspired 'Charlotte's Web' Medical Marijuana Oil Dies at 13 |url=https://time.com/5817682/charlotte-figi-dies-marijuana-oil-13/ |publisher=Time |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Because of her story, she also gained worldwide notice and media attention.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2013, she was the subject of the CNN documentary ''Weed'' by [[Sanjay Gupta]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Naftulin |first1=Julia |title=Charlotte Figi, the girl who spurred a cannabis movement that changed laws across the world, dies at 13 after being treated as 'a likely COVID-19 case' |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/charlotte-figi-inspired-cannabis-movement-dies-at-13-from-coronavirus-2020-4 |publisher=Business Insider |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She became a well-known figure in the U.S. and international medical marijuana movement<ref name=\"Ingold_4/8/2020\">{{cite web |last1=Ingold |first1=John |title=Charlotte Figi, the Colorado girl who inspired the CBD movement, dies following illness suspected to be coronavirus |url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/04/08/charlotte-figi-cbd-coronavirus/ |newspaper=[[The Colorado Sun]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and her story helped support U.S. legislation on medical marijuana.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2019, Figi was the first child featured on a cover of ''[[High Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/charlotte-figi-dead-obit-cbd-medical-marijuana-980454/|title=Charlotte Figi, Poster Child for Medicinal Benefits of CBD, Dead at 13|last=Blistein|first=Jon|date=2020-04-08|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2020, Figi was hospitalized with pneumonia, which then caused seizures, respiratory failure, and cardiac arrest.<ref name=\"Shapiro_4/16/2020\">{{cite web | last=Shapiro | first=Katie | date=April 16, 2020 | title=Remembering Charlotte Figi, a hero of the CBD movement | website=[[The Aspen Times]] | url=https://www.aspentimes.com/news/high-country-remembering-charlotte-figi-a-hero-of-the-cbd-movement/ | accessdate=April 18, 2020 }}</ref> She died on April 7, 2020, at the age of 13. According to her mother, Figi was admitted to the hospital and tested negative for [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on April 3, and was \"treated as a likely COVID-19 case\" when later readmitted to the hospital.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Dara Bitler |author2=Ashley Michels |title=Colorado girl who pioneered medical marijuana for seizures dies following seizure, likely COVID-19 case |url=https://kdvr.com/news/coronavirus/colorado-girl-who-pioneered-medical-marijuana-for-seizures-dies-of-coronavirus/ |publisher=KDVR |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Garcia_4/10/2020\">{{cite web | last=Garcia | first=Sandra E | title=Charlotte Figi, Who Helped Popularize CBD for Medical Use, Dies at 13 | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 10, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/us/charlotte-figi-dead.html | access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Portal|Biography|Cannabis}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Figi, Charlotte}}\n[[Category:2006 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:American people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:American twin children]]\n[[Category:Cannabis in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Deaths from epilepsy]]\n[[Category:Neurological disease deaths in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Colorado Springs, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Women in cannabis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Charlotte Figi\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|2006|10|18}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2020|04|07|2006|10|18}} \n| death_place   = [[Colorado Springs]], [[U.S.]]\n| nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n{{short description|American medical cannabidiol patient}}\n'''Charlotte Figi''' (October 18, 2006 \u2013 April 7, 2020) was an American girl with [[Dravet syndrome]] who took [[cannabidiol]] (CBD) oil to prevent seizures and inspired the name of the medical cannabis strain called [[Charlotte's web (cannabis)|Charlotte's Web]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/charlotte-figi-girl-severe-seizures-inspired-cbd-treatments-dies-13-n1179396|title=Charlotte Figi, girl with severe seizures that inspired CBD treatments, dies at 13|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n\nFigi was born on October 18, 2006, with a twin sister, to parents Paige and Matt Figi.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Saundra |title=Marijuana stops child's severe seizures |url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/08/07/health/charlotte-child-medical-marijuana/index.html |publisher=CNN |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=August 7, 2013}}</ref> At 3 months old, she had her first seizure.<ref name=\":5\" /> Due to her Dravet syndrome, at age five, she used a wheelchair, had up to 300 [[grand mal seizures]] a week, and had trouble speaking.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last1=Slevin |first1=Colleen |title=Girl Who Inspired Charlotte's Web Marijuana Oil Dies |url=https://apnews.com/f19a91d58ab50fad1ca2267f53ae3696 |publisher=The Associated Press |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, Figi's mother searched for CBD marijuana oil for her daughter's treatment.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |last1=Philipps |first1=Dave |title=Bid to Expand Medical Marijuana Business Faces Federal Hurdles |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/24/us/bid-to-expand-medical-marijuana-business-faces-federal-hurdles.html?searchResultPosition=3 |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |date=August 23, 2014}}</ref> Figi began taking oil from the marijuana plant, \"Hippie\u2019s Disappointment,\" which contained low THC<ref name=\":3\" /> and was later renamed Charlotte's Web.<ref name=\":2\" /> With the use of Charlotte's Web, Figi experienced an immediate reduction in her epileptic seizures, down from 300 a week to two or three per month.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web |last1=Osborne |first1=Hannah |title=Charlotte Figi: The Girl Who is Changing Medical Marijuana Laws Across America |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/charlotte-figi-girl-who-changing-medical-marijuana-laws-across-america-1453547 |publisher=International Business Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> While the use of medical marijuana was still illegal in many states, news of Figi\u2019s success spread and families with similar diagnoses started moving to Colorado Springs, where the drug was originally sold.<ref>{{cite web |title=Moving for marijuana: Families with seizure-stricken kids relocating to Colorado for strain of pot |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/health/kids-seizure-charlotte-web-pot-treatment-article-1.1619066 |publisher=New York Daily News |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=February 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Colorado Girl Who Inspired 'Charlotte's Web' Medical Marijuana Oil Dies at 13 |url=https://time.com/5817682/charlotte-figi-dies-marijuana-oil-13/ |publisher=Time |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Because of her story, she also gained worldwide notice and media attention.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2013, she was the subject of the CNN documentary ''Weed'' by [[Sanjay Gupta]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Naftulin |first1=Julia |title=Charlotte Figi, the girl who spurred a cannabis movement that changed laws across the world, dies at 13 after being treated as 'a likely COVID-19 case' |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/charlotte-figi-inspired-cannabis-movement-dies-at-13-from-coronavirus-2020-4 |publisher=Business Insider |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She became a well-known figure in the U.S. and international medical marijuana movement<ref name=\"Ingold_4/8/2020\">{{cite web |last1=Ingold |first1=John |title=Charlotte Figi, the Colorado girl who inspired the CBD movement, dies following illness suspected to be coronavirus |url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/04/08/charlotte-figi-cbd-coronavirus/ |newspaper=[[The Colorado Sun]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and her story helped support U.S. legislation on medical marijuana.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2019, Figi was the first child featured on a cover of ''[[High Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/charlotte-figi-dead-obit-cbd-medical-marijuana-980454/|title=Charlotte Figi, Poster Child for Medicinal Benefits of CBD, Dead at 13|last=Blistein|first=Jon|date=2020-04-08|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2020, Figi was hospitalized with pneumonia, which then caused seizures, respiratory failure, and cardiac arrest.<ref name=\"Shapiro_4/16/2020\">{{cite web | last=Shapiro | first=Katie | date=April, 16 2020 | title=Remembering Charlotte Figi, a hero of the CBD movement | website=[[The Aspen Times]] | url=https://www.aspentimes.com/news/high-country-remembering-charlotte-figi-a-hero-of-the-cbd-movement/ | accessdate=April 18, 2020 }}</ref> She died on April 7, 2020, at the age of 13. According to her mother, Figi was admitted to the hospital and tested negative for [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on April 3, and was \"treated as a likely COVID-19 case\" when later readmitted to the hospital.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Dara Bitler |author2=Ashley Michels |title=Colorado girl who pioneered medical marijuana for seizures dies following seizure, likely COVID-19 case |url=https://kdvr.com/news/coronavirus/colorado-girl-who-pioneered-medical-marijuana-for-seizures-dies-of-coronavirus/ |publisher=KDVR |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Garcia_4/10/2020\">{{cite web | last=Garcia | first=Sandra E | title=Charlotte Figi, Who Helped Popularize CBD for Medical Use, Dies at 13 | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 10, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/us/charlotte-figi-dead.html | access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Portal|Biography|Cannabis}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Figi, Charlotte}}\n[[Category:2006 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:American people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:American twin children]]\n[[Category:Cannabis in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Deaths from epilepsy]]\n[[Category:Neurological disease deaths in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Colorado Springs, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Women in cannabis]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Move comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlotte_Figi"}
{"title_page": "Welis H. Blodgett", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Wells H. Blodgett\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1839|01|29}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1929|05|08|1839|01|29}}\n|birth_place   = Downer's Grove, Illinois\n|death_place   = [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\n|placeofburial = \n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = \n|rank          = First Lieutenant\n|unit          = {{Flagicon|Illinois}} [[37th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Infantry ]] - Company D \n|battles       = [[First Battle of Newtonia]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\nFirst Lieutenant '''Wells H. Blodgett''' (January 29, 1839 to May 8, 1929)<ref name=\"Project\">{{Cite web |url=http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=3101 |title=Wells A. Blodgett}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://valor.defense.gov/Recipients/ArmyMedalofHonorRecipients.aspx |title=U.S. Army Medal of Honor recipients |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> Blodgett received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action during the [[First Battle of Newtonia]] in [[Missouri]] on 30 September 1862. He was honored with the award on 15 February 1894.<ref name=\"Find\">{{Cite web |url=http://medal-of-honor.findthedata.org/l/103/Blodgett |title=First Lieutenant Wells H. Blodgett |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBlodgett was born in [[Downer's Grove, Illinois]] on January 29, 1839 to Israel and Avis Blodgett, two early settlers of DuPage County. He joined the Union army in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. He died on 8 May 1929.\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|With a single orderly, captured an armed picket of 8 men and marched them in prisoners.<ref name=\"Project\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blodgett, Wells H.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Wells H. Blodgett\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1839|01|29}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1929|05|08|1839|01|29}}\n|birth_place   = Downer's Grove, Illinois\n|death_place   = [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\n|placeofburial = \n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = \n|rank          = First Lieutenant\n|unit          = {{Flagicon|Illinois}} Company D, 37th Illinois Infantry \n|battles       = [[First Battle of Newtonia]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\nFirst Lieutenant '''Wells H. Blodgett''' (January 29, 1839 to May 8, 1929)<ref name=\"Project\">{{Cite web |url=http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=3101 |title=Wells A. Blodgett}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://valor.defense.gov/Recipients/ArmyMedalofHonorRecipients.aspx |title=U.S. Army Medal of Honor recipients |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> Blodgett received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action during the [[First Battle of Newtonia]] in [[Missouri]] on 30 September 1862. He was honored with the award on 15 February 1894.<ref name=\"Find\">{{Cite web |url=http://medal-of-honor.findthedata.org/l/103/Blodgett |title=First Lieutenant Wells H. Blodgett |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBlodgett was born in [[Downer's Grove, Illinois]] on January 29, 1839 to Israel and Avis Blodgett, two early settlers of DuPage County. He joined the Union army in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. He died on 8 May 1929.\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|With a single orderly, captured an armed picket of 8 men and marched them in prisoners.<ref name=\"Project\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blodgett, Wells H.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welis_H._Blodgett"}
{"title_page": "Theda Bara", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Theda Bara\n| image         = Theda Bara 1921 Orval Hixon.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Bara in 1921\n| birth_name    = Theodosia Burr Goodman\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1885|7|29|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1955|4|7|1885|7|29|mf=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| resting_place = [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park Cemetery, Glendale]]\n| nationality   = American\n| education     = [[Walnut Hills High School]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Cincinnati]]\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 1908\u20131926\n| spouse        = {{Marriage|[[Charles Brabin]]|1921}}\n}}\n\n'''Theda Bara''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u03b8|i\u02d0|d|\u0259|_|\u02c8|b|\u00e6r|\u0259}} {{respell|THEE|d\u0259|_|BARR|\u0259}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fVBLHr4iwVM|title=Theda Bara Speaking 1936|website=[[YouTube]]|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> born '''Theodosia Burr Goodman'''; July 29, 1885&nbsp;\u2013 April 7, 1955) was an American [[silent film]] and stage actress.<ref name=obit/>\n\nBara was one of the more popular actresses of the silent era and one of cinema's early [[sex symbol]]s. Her [[femme fatale]] roles earned her the nickname \"The Vamp\" (short for vampire),{{efn|These roles did not portray the [[undead]] [[Vampire films|vampires]] featured in later horror films. The term \"vampire\" for a seductive woman was derived from \"The Vampire\", an 1897 poem by [[Rudyard Kipling]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Golden|first=Eve|author-link=Eve Golden|title=Vamp: The Rise and Fall of Theda Bara|location=Vestal, New York|publisher=Emprise|year=1996|isbn=1-887322-00-0|oclc=34575681|page=30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Weinstock|first=Jeffrey|title=The Vampire Film : Undead Cinema|date=2012|publisher=[[Columbia University Press|Wallflower Press]]|location=[[London, UK]]|page=25}}</ref>}} later fueling the rising popularity in \"vamp\" roles that encapsulated exoticism and sexual domination.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Love|first1=Claire|last2=Pollack|first2=Jen|last3=Landsberg|first3=Alison|title=Silent Film Actresses and Their Most Popular Characters|publisher=National Women's History Museum|date=April 6, 2017|url=https://www.womenshistory.org/articles/silent-film-actresses-and-their-most-popular-characters|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> Bara made more than 40 films between 1914 and 1926, but most were [[Lost film|lost]] in the [[1937 Fox vault fire]]. After her marriage to [[Charles Brabin]] in 1921, she made two more feature films and then retired from acting in 1926, never appearing in a sound film.\n\n==Early life==\nBara was born Theodosia Burr Goodman on July 29, 1885 in the Avondale section of Cincinnati, Ohio.<ref name=obit/> Her father was Bernard Goodman (1853\u20131936),<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|title=Theda makes 'em all Baras|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1917/11/17/102375105.pdf|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 17, 1917}}</ref> a prosperous [[Jews|Jewish]] tailor born in [[Polish people|Poland]]. Her mother, Pauline Louise Fran\u00e7oise (n\u00e9e de Coppett; 1861\u20131957), was born in Switzerland.<ref>{{cite book|last=Genini|first=Ronald|title=Theda Bara: A Biography of the Silent Screen Vamp, with a Filmography|publisher=McFarland|year=1996|isbn=9780786491612|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cmwfPXTQNSwC&pg=PA1848&lpg=PA1848&dq=de+Coppet+%22Pauline+Louise+Fran%C3%A7oise%22}}</ref> Bernard and Pauline married in 1882. Theda had two younger siblings: Marque (1888\u20131954)<ref>{{cite news|title=Marque Bara|work=Newport Daily News|location=Newport, Rhode Island)|date=April 26, 1954|page=2}}</ref> and Esther (1897\u20131965),<ref name=\"NYT\"/> who also became a film actress under the name of Lori Bara. She was named after the daughter of [[Vice President of the United States|US Vice President]] [[Aaron Burr]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/the-dramatic-life-and-mysterious-death-of-theodosia-burr|title=The Dramatic Life and Mysterious Death of Theodosia Burr|access-date=October 8, 2019|publisher=[[Atlas Obscura]]}}</ref>\n\nBara attended [[Walnut Hills High School (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Walnut Hills High School]], graduating in 1903. After attending the University of Cincinnati for two years, she worked mainly in local theater productions, but did explore other projects. After moving to New York City in 1908, she made her Broadway debut the same year in ''The Devil''.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Career==\nMost of Bara's early films were shot along the East Coast, where the film industry was centered at that time, primarily at the [[Fox Studios]] in [[Fort Lee, New Jersey]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Fort Lee: Birthplace of the Motion Picture Industry|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2006|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ViR3b72xkK0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Fort+Lee:+Birthplace+of+the+Motion+Picture+Industry#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=978-0-7385-4501-1}}</ref>\n\nBara lived with her family in New York City during this time. The rise of Hollywood as the center of the American film industry forced her to relocate to Los Angeles to film the epic ''[[Cleopatra (1917 film)|Cleopatra]]'' (1917), which became one of Bara's biggest hits. [[Lost films|No known prints of ''Cleopatra'' exist today]], but numerous photographs of Bara in costume as the Queen of the Nile have survived.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n[[File:Theda Bara, A Fool There Was (1915) Publicity Still.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=|Bara in ''[[A Fool There Was (1915 film)|A Fool There Was]]'' (1915)]]\n\nBetween 1915 and 1919, Bara was Fox studio's biggest star; but, tired of being typecast as a vamp, she allowed her five-year contract with Fox to expire. Her final Fox film was ''The Lure of Ambition'' (1919). In 1920, she turned briefly to the stage, appearing on Broadway in ''[[The Blue Flame (play)|The Blue Flame]]''. Bara's fame drew large crowds to the theater, but her acting was savaged by critics.<ref>{{cite book|last=Golden|first=Eve|author-link=Eve Golden|title=Vamp: The Rise and Fall of Theda Bara|location=Vestal, New York|publisher=Emprise|year=1996|isbn=1-887322-00-0|oclc=34575681|pages=204\u2013209}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The She Devil 1918.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=|Bara in ''[[The She-Devil]]'' (1918)]]\n\nHer career suffered without Fox studio's support, and she did not make another film until ''[[The Unchastened Woman]]'' (1925) for [[Chadwick Pictures]]. Bara retired after making only one more film, the short comedy ''[[Madame Mystery]]'' (1926), made for [[Hal Roach]] and directed by [[Stan Laurel]], in which she parodied her vamp image.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nAt the height of her fame, Bara earned $4,000 per week (the equivalent of over $56,000 per week in 2017 adjusted dollars).<!--She was one of the more popular movie stars, ranking behind only [[Charlie Chaplin]] and [[Mary Pickford]].<ref>http://oncotton.co.uk/starr/documents/THEDAprogramme&PDF.pdf  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901030944/http://oncotton.co.uk/starr/documents/THEDAprogramme&PDF.pdf|date=September 1, 2012}}</ref>--> Bara's better-known roles were as the \"vamp\", although she attempted to avoid typecasting by playing wholesome heroines in films such as ''Under Two Flags'' and ''Her Double Life''. She appeared as Juliet in a version of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]''. Although Bara took her craft seriously, she was too successful as an exotic \"wanton woman\" to develop a more versatile career.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n===Image and name===\nThe origin of Bara's stage name is disputed; ''The Guinness Book of Movie Facts and Feats'' says it came from director [[Frank Powell]], who learned Theda had a relative named Barranger, and that Theda was a childhood nickname. In promoting the 1917 film ''[[Cleopatra (1917 film)|Cleopatra]]'', Fox Studio publicists noted that the name was an anagram of ''Arab death'', and her press agents, to enhance her exotic appeal to moviegoers, falsely promoted the young Ohio native as \"the daughter of an Arab sheik and a French woman, born in the [[Sahara]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/87424/Cleopatra/overview|title=Cleopatra (1917)|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=May 29, 2011}} Film review.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qYEtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WZkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7227,1426917&dq=arab-death+theda-bara&hl=en|title=Famous Silent Screen Vamp Theda Bara Dies Of Cancer|agency=[[Associated Press]]|newspaper=The Montreal Gazette|date=April 8, 1955|access-date=May 29, 2011}}</ref> In 1917, the Goodman family legally changed its surname to Bara.<ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\n==Persona==\nBara was known for wearing very revealing costumes in her films. Such outfits were banned from Hollywood films after the [[Motion Picture Production Code|Production Code]] (a.k.a. the Hays Code) started in 1930, and then was more strongly enforced in 1934. It was popular at that time to promote an actress as mysterious, with an exotic background. The studios promoted Bara with a massive publicity campaign, billing her as the Egyptian-born daughter of a French actress and an Italian sculptor. They claimed she had spent her early years in the Sahara desert under the shadow of the [[Sphinx]], then moved to France to become a stage actress. (In fact, Bara never had been to Egypt, and her time in France amounted to just a few months.) They called her the \"Serpent of the Nile\" and encouraged her to discuss mysticism and the occult in interviews. Some film historians point to this as the birth of two Hollywood phenomena: the studio publicity department and the press agent (later evolving into the public relations person).{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nA 2016 book by Joan Craig with Beverly F. Stout chronicles many personal, first-hand accounts of the lives of Theda Bara and Charles Brabin.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Craig|first1=Joan|last2=Stout|first2=Beverly F.|title=Theda Bara, My Mentor: Under the Wing of Hollywood's First Femme Fatale|publisher=McFarland and Company, Inc.|year=2016|isbn=9781476662831|lccn=2016009417}}</ref> It reveals a great dichotomy between Theda Bara's screen persona and her real-life persona. Included are Bara's surprised responses to the critical reactions to her screen portrayals from a sector of the community. The author was befriended by Theda Bara and Charles Brabin beginning when she was a young girl. Ms. Craig's photographic-like memory paints an important picture of how they lived, where they lived, and what they said and did, even to the point of describing in great detail most of the rooms of their house. The book describes how Ms. Bara, who learned pattern making and wig making from her mother and father, designed and created most of the costumes and gowns she wore in her films, including the striking costumes she wore in ''Cleopatra''.\n\n==Marriage and retirement==\n[[File:Theda Bara & Charles Brabin 1922.jpg|thumb|upright|Bara with [[Charles Brabin]], 1922]]\nBara married British-born American film director [[Charles Brabin]] in 1921. They honeymooned at [[Digby Pines Golf Resort and Spa|The Pines Hotel]] in Digby, Nova Scotia, Canada, and later purchased a {{convert|400|ha|adj=on}} property down the coast from Digby at Harbourville, Nova Scotia, overlooking the [[Bay of Fundy]], eventually building a summer home they called Baranook.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/thenovascotian/67331-hollywood-s-link-province-long-varied|title=Hollywood's link with province long, varied|last=Innis|first=Lorna|newspaper=Chronicle Herald|location=Halifax|date=February 26, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517115531/http://thechronicleherald.ca/thenovascotian/67331-hollywood-s-link-province-long-varied|archive-date=May 17, 2014|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> They had no children. Bara resided in a villa-style home in Cincinnati, which served as the \"honors villa\" at Xavier University. Demolition of the home began in July 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2011/07/07/film-star-home-torn-down-cincinnati.html|title=Early film star's Cincinnati mansion being torn down|newspaper=The Columbus Post Dispatch|date=July 7, 2011|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1936, she appeared on ''[[Lux Radio Theatre]]'' during a broadcast version of ''[[The Thin Man]]'' with [[William Powell]] and [[Myrna Loy]]. She did not appear in the play but instead announced her plans to make a movie comeback,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/LuxRadioTheater360608TheThinMan|title=The Thin Man|website=Lux Radio Theatre|publisher=Internet Archive|access-date=December 1, 2015}} Skip to 50m:50s.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=The+Lux+Radio+Theatre|title=The Lux Radio Theatre|publisher=RadioGOLDINdex|access-date=December 1, 2015}}</ref> which never materialized. She appeared on radio again in 1939 as a guest on ''[[Texaco Star Theatre]]''.\n\nIn 1949, producer [[Buddy DeSylva]] and [[Columbia Pictures]] expressed interest in making a movie of Bara's life to star [[Betty Hutton]], but the project never materialized.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brady|first=Thomas F.|title=De Sylva Working on Movie of Bara|newspaper=The New York Times|date=January 21, 1949|page=25|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B05E4D9123CE23BBC4951DFB7668382659EDE}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Brady|first=Thomas F.|title=Betty Hutton Set for 2 Metro Films|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 2, 1949|page=36|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E06E5D61E3BE23BBC4A53DFB4678382659EDE}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Theda Bara Grave.JPG|thumb|upright|Bara's niche in the Great Mausoleum, Forest Lawn Glendale]]\nOn April 7, 1955, after a lengthy stay at California Lutheran Hospital in Los Angeles, Bara died there of stomach cancer.<ref name=obit>{{cite news|title=Theda Bara, Screen Star, 68. 'Siren' of Silent Films Was Top Box-Office Attraction During the Twenties Denounced in Churches 'Cleopatra' 'The Vampire,' 'Salome' And 'Madame Du Barry' Among Her Hits Screen 'Vampire'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/04/08/archives/tdabarad1es-screen-star-68-siren-of-silent-films-was-top-boxoffice.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 8, 1955}}</ref> She was survived by her husband Charles Brabin, her mother, and sister Lori.<ref name=obit/> She was interred as Theda Bara Brabin at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park Cemetery]] in Glendale, California.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rites for Theda Bara Today|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/04/09/archives/kites-for-theda-bara-today.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 9, 1955|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nBara often is cited as the first [[sex symbol]] of the film era.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicimages.com/1996/july/theda.html|title=Classic Images&nbsp;\u2013 Vol. 250&nbsp;\u2013 April 1996 Issue|publisher=Classicimages.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716222612/http://www.classicimages.com/1996/july/theda.html|archive-date=July 16, 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Mondo Exotica: Sounds, Visions, Obsessions of the Cocktail Generation|last=Adinolfi|first=Francesco|date=2008|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822341321|location=Durham|page=25|translator-last=Pinkus|translator-first=Karen|oclc=179838406|translator-last2=Vivrette|translator-first2=Jason}}</ref>\n\nFor her contributions to the film industry, Bara received a [[List of actors with Hollywood Walk of Fame motion picture stars|motion pictures star]] on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in 1960. Her star is located at 6307 Hollywood Boulevard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/theda-bara|title=Theda Bara|website=Hollywood Walk of Fame|publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce|access-date=September 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe is one of the more famous completely silent stars\u2014she never appeared in a sound film, lost or otherwise. A 1937 fire at Fox's nitrate film storage vaults in New Jersey destroyed most of that studio's silent films. Bara made more than 40 films between 1914 and 1926, but complete prints of only six still exist: ''[[The Stain (film)|The Stain]]'' (1914), ''[[A Fool There Was (1915 film)|A Fool There Was]]'' (1915), ''[[East Lynne (1916 film)|East Lynne]]'' (1916), ''[[The Unchastened Woman]]'' (1925), and two short comedies for [[Hal Roach]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nIn addition to these, a few of her films remain in fragments, including ''Cleopatra'' (just a few seconds of footage), a clip thought to be from ''The Soul of Buddha'', and a few other unidentified clips featured in the documentary ''Theda Bara et William Fox'' (2001). Most of the clips can be seen in the documentary ''The Woman with the Hungry Eyes'' (2006). As to vamping, critics stated that her portrayal of calculating, cold-hearted women was morally instructive to men. Bara responded by saying \"I will continue doing vampires as long as people sin.\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Sexy Origins and Intimate Things: The Rites and Rituals of Straights, Gays, Bi's, Drags, Trans, Virgins, and Others|last=Panati|first=Charles|author-link=Charles Panati|year=1998|publisher=Penguin Books|page=295}}</ref> Additional footage has been found which shows her behind the scenes on a picture.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://ngataonga.org.nz/collections/catalogue/catalogue-item?record_id=79334|title=Fads and Fashion of 1900 [& Other Newsreels]|medium=film|year=1905|publisher=Fun Film|minutes=8|via=[[Ng\u0101 Taonga Sound & Vision]]}}</ref> While the hairstyle has led some to theorize that this may be from ''[[The Lure of Ambition]]'', this has not been confirmed.\n\nIn 1994, she was honored with her image on a [[List of people on the postage stamps of the United States|U.S. postage stamp]] designed by caricaturist [[Al Hirschfeld]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=March 26, 1994|title=Hirschfeld draws silent screen stars stamps|journal=Stamps|volume=246|issue=13|pages=353|id={{ProQuest|220978182}}}}</ref> The Fort Lee Film Commission dedicated Main Street and Linwood Avenue in [[Fort Lee, New Jersey]] as \"Theda Bara Way\" in May 2006 to honor Bara, who made many of her films at the Fox Studio on Linwood and Main.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A421124059|title=A Star in the Era Before Hollywood|last=Page|first=Jeffery|date=July 9, 2015|work=The Record|access-date=August 21, 2019|via=Gale Onefile:News}}</ref>\n\nOver a period of several years, filmmaker and film historian Phillip Dye reconstructed ''Cleopatra'' on video. Titled ''Lost Cleopatra'', the full-length feature was created by editing together production-still picture montages combined with the surviving film clip. The script was based on the original scenario with modifications derived from research into censorship reports, reviews of the film, and synopses from period magazines.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Lost Cleopatra|url=http://www.lostcleopatra.com|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> Dye screened the film at the [[Hollywood Heritage Museum]] on February 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ziemba|first=Christine N.|website=LAist|date=February 6, 2017|url=http://laist.com/2017/02/06/20_of_the_coolest_events_happening_2.php|title=Twenty Of The Coolest Events Happening in L.A. This Week in Arts & Entertainment|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501083710/http://laist.com/2017/02/06/20_of_the_coolest_events_happening_2.php|archive-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Romeo and juliet1916.jpg|thumb|upright|From ''[[Romeo and Juliet (1916 Fox film)|Romeo and Juliet]]'' (1916); standing, L-R: Helen Tracy (Lady Capulet), [[Alice Gale]] (Nurse), and Edward Holt (Capulet); seated: Bara as Juliet]]\n[[File:Alan Roscoe-Theda Bara in Camille.jpg|thumb|upright|Bara with [[Alan Roscoe]] in ''[[Camille (1917 film)|Camille]]'' (1917)]]\n[[File:ThedaBara-Cleopatra.jpg|thumb|upright|Bara in ''Cleopatra'' (1917)]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1914\n| ''[[The Stain (film)|The Stain]]''\n| Gang moll\n| Credited as Theodosia Goodman\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[A Fool There Was (1915 film)|A Fool There Was]]''\n| The Vampire\n|\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[The Kreutzer Sonata (1915 film)|The Kreutzer Sonata]]''\n| Celia Friedlander\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[The Clemenceau Case]]''\n| Iza\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[The Devil's Daughter (1915 film)|The Devil's Daughter]]''\n| Gioconda Dianti\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[Lady Audley's Secret (1915 film)|Lady Audley's Secret]]''\n| Helen Talboys\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[The Two Orphans (1915 film)|The Two Orphans]]''\n| Henriette\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[Sin (1915 film)|Sin]]''\n| Rosa\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[Carmen (1915 Raoul Walsh film)|Carmen]]''\n| [[Carmen]]\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[The Galley Slave]]''\n| Francesca Brabaut\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[Destruction (film)|Destruction]]''\n| Fernade\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1916\n| ''[[The Serpent (1916 film)|The Serpent]]''\n| Vania Lazar\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1916\n| ''[[Gold and the Woman]]''\n| Theresa Decordova\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1916\n| ''[[The Eternal Sapho]]''\n| Laura Bruffins\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1916\n| ''[[East Lynne (1916 film)|East Lynne]]''\n| Lady Isabel Carlisle\n|\n|-\n| 1916\n| ''[[Under Two Flags (1916 film)|Under Two Flags]]''\n| Cigarette\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1916\n| ''[[Her Double Life]]''\n| Mary Doone\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1916\n| ''[[Romeo and Juliet (1916 Fox film)|Romeo and Juliet]]''\n| [[Juliet]]\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1916\n| ''[[The Vixen]]''\n| Elsie Drummond\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1917\n| ''[[The Darling of Paris]]''\n| [[Esmeralda (The Hunchback of Notre Dame)|Esmeralda]]\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1917\n| ''[[The Tiger Woman (1917 film)|The Tiger Woman]]''\n| Princess Petrovitch\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1917\n| ''[[Her Greatest Love]]''\n| Hazel\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1917\n| ''[[Heart and Soul (1917 film)|Heart and Soul]]''\n| Jess\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1917\n| ''[[Camille (1917 film)|Camille]]''\n| [[La Dame aux Cam\u00e9lias|Marguerite Gauthier]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Theda Bara Makes 'Camille' Reality|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/access/828058332.html?dids=828058332:828058332&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&date=Oct+30%2C+1917&author=&pub=The+Hartford+Courant&desc=THEDA+BARA+MAKES+%27CAMILLE%27+REALITY&pqatl=google|quote=Heralded as one of the screen triumphs of the day, \"Camille\", adapted from the Dumas novel, and with Theda Bara the featured player, fulfills the promises of the management of Poli's Theater, where this film really heads the bill this half of the week. Vaudeville must...|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=October 30, 1917|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831233742/https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/access/828058332.html?dids=828058332:828058332&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&date=Oct+30%2C+1917&author=&pub=The+Hartford+Courant&desc=THEDA+BARA+MAKES+%27CAMILLE%27+REALITY&pqatl=google|archive-date=August 31, 2012|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1917\n| ''[[Cleopatra (1917 film)|Cleopatra]]''\n| [[Cleopatra]]\n| Approximately 20&nbsp;seconds exist\n|-\n| 1917\n| ''[[The Rose of Blood]]''\n| Lisza Tapenka\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1917\n| ''[[Madame Du Barry (1917 film)|Madame Du Barry]]''\n| [[Madame du Barry|Jeanne Vaubernier]]\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1918\n| ''[[The Forbidden Path]]''\n| Mary Lynde\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1918\n| ''[[The Soul of Buddha]]''\n| Priestess\n| Story, Lost film\n|-\n| 1918\n| ''[[Under the Yoke (film)|Under the Yoke]]''\n| Maria Valverda\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1918\n| ''[[Salom\u00e9 (1918 film)|Salom\u00e9]]''\n| [[Salome (opera)|Salome]]\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1918\n| ''[[When a Woman Sins]]''\n| Lilian Marchard / Poppea\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1918\n| ''[[The She-Devil]]''\n| Lorette\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1919\n| ''The Light''\n| Blanchette Dumond, aka Madame Lefresne\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1919\n| ''[[When Men Desire]]''\n| Marie Lohr\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1919\n| ''[[The Siren's Song (1919 film)|The Siren's Song]]''\n| Marie Bernais\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1919\n| ''[[A Woman There Was]]''\n| Princess Zara\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1919\n| ''[[Kathleen Mavourneen (1919 film)|Kathleen Mavourneen]]''\n| Kathleen Cavanagh\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1919\n| ''[[La Belle Russe]]''\n| Fleurett Sackton/La Belle Russe\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1919\n| ''[[Lure of Ambition|The Lure of Ambition]]''\n| Olga Dolan\n| Lost film; 82-second outtake does exist<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cXCendCga10|title=Lost Film segment - Theda Bara - 1919 (currently unknown film source)|website=[[YouTube]]|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1925\n| ''[[The Unchastened Woman]]''\n| Caroline Knollys\n|\n|-\n| 1926\n| ''[[Madame Mystery]]''\n| Madame Mysterieux\n| Short film\n|-\n| 1926\n| ''[[45 Minutes from Hollywood]]''\n| Herself\n| Short film\n|}\n\n==Cultural references==\n{{in popular culture|date=February 2018}}\nBara was one of three actresses ([[Pola Negri]] and [[Mae Murray]] were the others) whose eyes were combined to form the [[Chicago International Film Festival]]'s logo, a stark, black and white close up of the composite eyes set as repeated frames in a strip of film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagofilmfestival.com/about-us/mission-history/|title=About: Mission & History Our Logo|publisher=The Chicago International Film Festival|at=Our Logo|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[International Times]]''{{'}} logo is a black-and-white image of Theda Bara. The founders' intention had been to use an image of actress [[Clara Bow]], 1920s \"[[It girl]]\", but a picture of Theda Bara was used by accident, and once deployed, not changed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Miles|first=Barry|author-link=Barry Miles|title=Many Years From Now|publisher=[[Vintage (publisher)|Vintage]] \u2013 [[Random House]]|year=1998|isbn=0-7493-8658-4|page=232|title-link=Many Years From Now}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1996, two biographies of Bara were released: Ron Genini's ''Theda Bara: A Biography'' (McFarland) and [[Eve Golden]]'s ''Vamp'' (Emprise). In October 2005 TimeLine Films of [[Culver City, California|Culver City]] premiered the film biography ''Theda Bara: The Woman with the Hungry Eyes''.\n\nBara has been the subject of several works of fiction, including ''In Theda Bara's Tent'' by Diana Altman, ''The Director's Cut: A Theda Bara Mystery'' by Christopher DiGrazia, and the play ''Theda Bara and the Frontier Rabbi'' by Bob Johnston.\n\nBara appears as a character in the books ''Vampyres of Hollywood'' and ''Love Bites'' by [[Adrienne Barbeau]], and in ''Coldheart Canyon: A Hollywood Ghost Story'' by [[Clive Barker]].\n\nIn season 2, episode 1 of ''[[The Lucy Show]]'', Vivian Bagley and Lucy argue over who should play Cleopatra in an upcoming play; Lucy states \"I've seen the movie twelve times!\" and Vivian quips \"She means the one with Theda Bara\".\n\nA photo of Bara as Cleopatra is the album artwork for [[The Lumineers]] record [[Cleopatra (album)|''Cleopatra'']] released in 2016.\n\nIn May 2016, a memoir titled ''Theda Bara, My Mentor, Under the Wings of Hollywood's First Femme Fatale'', by Joan Craig with Beverly Stout, was released. Young Joan, in the companionship of Bara during the 1940s and 1950s, includes tales of Bara's husband, Charles Brabin, friends [[Marion Davies]], [[Clark Gable]], [[Victor Fleming]], and other stars of the past.\n\nIn season 2, episode 7 of the television series ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', butler Carson describes the newly designed bathrooms at a nearby estate as \"like something out of a film with Theda Bara\".\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Shakespeare on Silent Film: An Excellent Dumb Discourse'' by [[Judith Buchanan]]. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2009. Chapter 6. {{ISBN|0-521-87199-9}}.\n* ''Famous Juliets'' by Jerome Hart, in ''Motion Picture Classic'', March 1923.\n* ''A Million and One Nights'' by Terry Ramsaye. New York: Simon and Schuster, 1926.\n* {{cite book|last=Fox|first=Susan|title=William Fox: A Story of Early Hollywood 1915\u20131930|publisher=Midnight Marquee Press Inc|year=2006|isbn=1-887664-62-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=DiGrazia|first=Christopher|title=The Director's Cut: A Theda Bara Mystery|publisher=1921 PVG Publishing|year=2011|isbn=978-0-9827709-4-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Johnston|first=Bob|title=Theda Bara and the Frontier Rabbi|publisher=Dramatist's Play Service|year=2002|isbn=0-8222-1837-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Altman|first=Diana|title=In Theda Bara's Tent|publisher=Tapley Cove Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0-615-34327-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|film}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Theda Bara}}\n* {{IMDb name|847}}\n* {{Amg name|3781}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120716222612/http://www.classicimages.com/1996/july/theda.html Excerpt from Golden's biography ''Vamp'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20030805031539/http://www.csse.monash.edu.au/~pringle/silent/ssotm/May96/ Biography at monash.edu.au]\n* [http://digitalgallery.nypl.org/nypldigital/dgkeysearchresult.cfm?parent_id=141370&word= Theda Bara] photo gallery NY Public Library Billy Rose collection\n* [http://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/bara-theda \"Theda Bara\"], entry in ''Jewish Women: A Comprehensive Historical Encyclopedia''\n\n{{Burlesque Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bara, Theda}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:American radio actresses]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from stomach cancer]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Theda Bara\n| image         = Theda Bara 1921 Orval Hixon.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Bara in 1921\n| birth_name    = Theodosia Burr Goodman\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1885|7|29|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1955|4|7|1885|7|29|mf=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| resting_place = [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park Cemetery, Glendale]]\n| nationality   = American\n| education     = [[Walnut Hills High School]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Cincinnati]]\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 1908\u20131926\n| spouse        = {{Marriage|[[Charles Brabin]]|1921}}\n}}\n\n'''Theda Bara''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u03b8|i\u02d0|d|\u0259|_|\u02c8|b|\u00e6r|\u0259}} {{respell|THEE|d\u0259|_|BARR|\u0259}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fVBLHr4iwVM|title=Theda Bara Speaking 1936|website=[[YouTube]]|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> born '''Theodosia Burr Goodman'''; July 29, 1885&nbsp;\u2013 April 7, 1955) was an American [[silent film]] and stage actress.<ref name=obit/>\n\nBara was one of the more popular actresses of the silent era and one of cinema's early [[sex symbol]]s. Her [[femme fatale]] roles earned her the nickname \"The Vamp\" (short for vampire),{{efn|These roles did not portray the [[undead]] [[Vampire films|vampires]] featured in later horror films. The term \"vampire\" for a seductive woman was derived from \"The Vampire\", an 1897 poem by [[Rudyard Kipling]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Golden|first=Eve|author-link=Eve Golden|title=Vamp: The Rise and Fall of Theda Bara|location=Vestal, New York|publisher=Emprise|year=1996|isbn=1-887322-00-0|oclc=34575681|page=30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Weinstock|first=Jeffrey|title=The Vampire Film : Undead Cinema|date=2012|publisher=[[Columbia University Press|Wallflower Press]]|location=[[London, UK]]|page=25}}</ref>}} later fueling the rising popularity in \"vamp\" roles that encapsulated exoticism and sexual domination.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Love|first1=Claire|last2=Pollack|first2=Jen|last3=Landsberg|first3=Alison|title=Silent Film Actresses and Their Most Popular Characters|publisher=National Women's History Museum|date=April 6, 2017|url=https://www.womenshistory.org/articles/silent-film-actresses-and-their-most-popular-characters|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> Bara made more than 40 films between 1914 and 1926, but most were [[Lost film|lost]] in the [[1937 Fox vault fire]]. After her marriage to [[Charles Brabin]] in 1921, she made two more feature films and then retired from acting in 1926, never appearing in a sound film.\n\n==Early life==\nBara was born Theodosia Burr Goodman on July 29, 1885 in the Avondale section of Cincinnati, Ohio.<ref name=obit/> Her father was Bernard Goodman (1853\u20131936),<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|title=Theda makes 'em all Baras|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1917/11/17/102375105.pdf|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 17, 1917}}</ref> a prosperous [[Jews|Jewish]] tailor born in [[Polish people|Poland]]. Her mother, Pauline Louise Fran\u00e7oise (n\u00e9e de Coppett; 1861\u20131957), was born in Switzerland.<ref>{{cite book|last=Genini|first=Ronald|title=Theda Bara: A Biography of the Silent Screen Vamp, with a Filmography|publisher=McFarland|year=1996|isbn=9780786491612|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cmwfPXTQNSwC&pg=PA1848&lpg=PA1848&dq=de+Coppet+%22Pauline+Louise+Fran%C3%A7oise%22}}</ref> Bernard and Pauline married in 1882. Theda had two younger siblings: Marque (1888\u20131954)<ref>{{cite news|title=Marque Bara|work=Newport Daily News|location=Newport, Rhode Island)|date=April 26, 1954|page=2}}</ref> and Esther (1897\u20131965),<ref name=\"NYT\"/> who also became a film actress under the name of Lori Bara. She was named after the daughter of [[Vice President of the United States|US Vice President]] [[Aaron Burr]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/the-dramatic-life-and-mysterious-death-of-theodosia-burr|title=The Dramatic Life and Mysterious Death of Theodosia Burr|access-date=October 8, 2019|publisher=[[Atlas Obscura]]}}</ref>\n\nBara attended [[Walnut Hills High School (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Walnut Hills High School]], graduating in 1903. After attending the University of Cincinnati for two years, she worked mainly in local theater productions, but did explore other projects. After moving to New York City in 1908, she made her Broadway debut the same year in ''The Devil''.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Career==\nMost of Bara's early films were shot along the East Coast, where the film industry was centered at that time, primarily at the [[Fox Studios]] in [[Fort Lee, New Jersey]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Fort Lee: Birthplace of the Motion Picture Industry|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2006|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ViR3b72xkK0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Fort+Lee:+Birthplace+of+the+Motion+Picture+Industry#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=978-0-7385-4501-1}}</ref>\n\nBara lived with her family in New York City during this time. The rise of Hollywood as the center of the American film industry forced her to relocate to Los Angeles to film the epic ''[[Cleopatra (1917 film)|Cleopatra]]'' (1917), which became one of Bara's biggest hits. [[Lost films|No known prints of ''Cleopatra'' exist today]], but numerous photographs of Bara in costume as the Queen of the Nile have survived.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n[[File:Theda Bara, A Fool There Was (1915) Publicity Still.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=|Bara in ''[[A Fool There Was (1915 film)|A Fool There Was]]'' (1915)]]\n\nBetween 1915 and 1919, Bara was Fox studio's biggest star; but, tired of being typecast as a vamp, she allowed her five-year contract with Fox to expire. Her final Fox film was ''The Lure of Ambition'' (1919). In 1920, she turned briefly to the stage, appearing on Broadway in ''[[The Blue Flame (play)|The Blue Flame]]''. Bara's fame drew large crowds to the theater, but her acting was savaged by critics.<ref>{{cite book|last=Golden|first=Eve|author-link=Eve Golden|title=Vamp: The Rise and Fall of Theda Bara|location=Vestal, New York|publisher=Emprise|year=1996|isbn=1-887322-00-0|oclc=34575681|pages=204\u2013209}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The She Devil 1918.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=|Bara in ''[[The She-Devil]]'' (1918)]]\n\nHer career suffered without Fox studio's support, and she did not make another film until ''[[The Unchastened Woman]]'' (1925) for [[Chadwick Pictures]]. Bara retired after making only one more film, the short comedy ''[[Madame Mystery]]'' (1926), made for [[Hal Roach]] and directed by [[Stan Laurel]], in which she parodied her vamp image.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nAt the height of her fame, Bara earned $4,000 per week (the equivalent of over $56,000 per week in 2017 adjusted dollars).<!--She was one of the more popular movie stars, ranking behind only [[Charlie Chaplin]] and [[Mary Pickford]].<ref>http://oncotton.co.uk/starr/documents/THEDAprogramme&PDF.pdf  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901030944/http://oncotton.co.uk/starr/documents/THEDAprogramme&PDF.pdf|date=September 1, 2012}}</ref>--> Bara's better-known roles were as the \"vamp\", although she attempted to avoid typecasting by playing wholesome heroines in films such as ''Under Two Flags'' and ''Her Double Life''. She appeared as Juliet in a version of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]''. Although Bara took her craft seriously, she was too successful as an exotic \"wanton woman\" to develop a more versatile career.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n===Image and name===\nThe origin of Bara's stage name is disputed; ''The Guinness Book of Movie Facts and Feats'' says it came from director [[Frank Powell]], who learned Theda had a relative named Barranger, and that Theda was a childhood nickname. In promoting the 1917 film ''[[Cleopatra (1917 film)|Cleopatra]]'', Fox Studio publicists noted that the name was an anagram of ''Arab death'', and her press agents, to enhance her exotic appeal to moviegoers, falsely promoted the young Ohio native as \"the daughter of an Arab sheik and a French woman, born in the [[Sahara]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/87424/Cleopatra/overview|title=Cleopatra (1917)|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=May 29, 2011}} Film review.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qYEtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WZkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7227,1426917&dq=arab-death+theda-bara&hl=en|title=Famous Silent Screen Vamp Theda Bara Dies Of Cancer|agency=[[Associated Press]]|newspaper=The Montreal Gazette|date=April 8, 1955|access-date=May 29, 2011}}</ref> In 1917, the Goodman family legally changed its surname to Bara.<ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\n==Persona==\nBara was known for wearing very revealing costumes in her films. Such outfits were banned from Hollywood films after the [[Motion Picture Production Code|Production Code]] (a.k.a. the Hays Code) started in 1930, and then was more strongly enforced in 1934. It was popular at that time to promote an actress as mysterious, with an exotic background. The studios promoted Bara with a massive publicity campaign, billing her as the Egyptian-born daughter of a French actress and an Italian sculptor. They claimed she had spent her early years in the Sahara desert under the shadow of the [[Sphinx]], then moved to France to become a stage actress. (In fact, Bara never had been to Egypt, and her time in France amounted to just a few months.) They called her the \"Serpent of the Nile\" and encouraged her to discuss mysticism and the occult in interviews. Some film historians point to this as the birth of two Hollywood phenomena: the studio publicity department and the press agent (later evolving into the public relations person).{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nA 2016 book, by Joan Craig with Beverly F. Stout, chronicles many personal, first-hand accounts of the lives of Theda Bara and Charles Brabin.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Craig|first1=Joan|last2=Stout|first2=Beverly F.|title=Theda Bara, My Mentor: Under the Wing of Hollywood's First Femme Fatale|publisher=McFarland and Company, Inc.|year=2016|isbn=9781476662831|lccn=2016009417}}</ref> It reveals a great dichotomy between Theda Bara's screen persona and her real-life persona. Included are Bara's surprised responses to the critical reactions to her screen portrayals from a sector of the community. The author was befriended by Theda Bara and Charles Brabin beginning when she was a young girl. Ms. Craig's photographic-like memory paints an important picture of how they lived, where they lived, and what they said and did, even to the point of describing in great detail most of the rooms of their house. The book describes how Ms. Bara, who learned pattern making and wig making from her mother and father, designed and created most of the costumes and gowns she wore in her films, including the striking costumes she wore in ''Cleopatra''.\n\n==Marriage and retirement==\n[[File:Theda Bara & Charles Brabin 1922.jpg|thumb|upright|Bara with [[Charles Brabin]], 1922]]\nBara married British-born American film director [[Charles Brabin]] in 1921. They honeymooned at [[Digby Pines Golf Resort and Spa|The Pines Hotel]] in Digby, Nova Scotia, Canada, and later purchased a {{convert|400|ha|adj=on}} property down the coast from Digby at Harbourville, Nova Scotia, overlooking the [[Bay of Fundy]], eventually building a summer home they called Baranook.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/thenovascotian/67331-hollywood-s-link-province-long-varied|title=Hollywood's link with province long, varied|last=Innis|first=Lorna|newspaper=Chronicle Herald|location=Halifax|date=February 26, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517115531/http://thechronicleherald.ca/thenovascotian/67331-hollywood-s-link-province-long-varied|archive-date=May 17, 2014|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> They had no children. Bara resided in a villa-style home in Cincinnati, which served as the \"honors villa\" at Xavier University. Demolition of the home began in July 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2011/07/07/film-star-home-torn-down-cincinnati.html|title=Early film star's Cincinnati mansion being torn down|newspaper=The Columbus Post Dispatch|date=July 7, 2011|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1936, she appeared on ''[[Lux Radio Theatre]]'' during a broadcast version of ''[[The Thin Man]]'' with [[William Powell]] and [[Myrna Loy]]. She did not appear in the play but instead announced her plans to make a movie comeback,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/LuxRadioTheater360608TheThinMan|title=The Thin Man|website=Lux Radio Theatre|publisher=Internet Archive|access-date=December 1, 2015}} Skip to 50m:50s.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=The+Lux+Radio+Theatre|title=The Lux Radio Theatre|publisher=RadioGOLDINdex|access-date=December 1, 2015}}</ref> which never materialized. She appeared on radio again in 1939 as a guest on ''[[Texaco Star Theatre]]''.\n\nIn 1949, producer [[Buddy DeSylva]] and [[Columbia Pictures]] expressed interest in making a movie of Bara's life to star [[Betty Hutton]], but the project never materialized.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brady|first=Thomas F.|title=De Sylva Working on Movie of Bara|newspaper=The New York Times|date=January 21, 1949|page=25|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B05E4D9123CE23BBC4951DFB7668382659EDE}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Brady|first=Thomas F.|title=Betty Hutton Set for 2 Metro Films|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 2, 1949|page=36|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E06E5D61E3BE23BBC4A53DFB4678382659EDE}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Theda Bara Grave.JPG|thumb|upright|Bara's niche in the Great Mausoleum, Forest Lawn Glendale]]\nOn April 7, 1955, after a lengthy stay at California Lutheran Hospital in Los Angeles, Bara died there of stomach cancer.<ref name=obit>{{cite news|title=Theda Bara, Screen Star, 68. 'Siren' of Silent Films Was Top Box-Office Attraction During the Twenties Denounced in Churches 'Cleopatra' 'The Vampire,' 'Salome' And 'Madame Du Barry' Among Her Hits Screen 'Vampire'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/04/08/archives/tdabarad1es-screen-star-68-siren-of-silent-films-was-top-boxoffice.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 8, 1955}}</ref> She was survived by her husband Charles Brabin, her mother, and sister Lori.<ref name=obit/> She was interred as Theda Bara Brabin at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park Cemetery]] in Glendale, California.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rites for Theda Bara Today|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/04/09/archives/kites-for-theda-bara-today.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 9, 1955|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nBara often is cited as the first [[sex symbol]] of the film era.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicimages.com/1996/july/theda.html|title=Classic Images&nbsp;\u2013 Vol. 250&nbsp;\u2013 April 1996 Issue|publisher=Classicimages.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716222612/http://www.classicimages.com/1996/july/theda.html|archive-date=July 16, 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Mondo Exotica: Sounds, Visions, Obsessions of the Cocktail Generation|last=Adinolfi|first=Francesco|date=2008|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822341321|location=Durham|page=25|translator-last=Pinkus|translator-first=Karen|oclc=179838406|translator-last2=Vivrette|translator-first2=Jason}}</ref>\n\nFor her contributions to the film industry, Bara received a [[List of actors with Hollywood Walk of Fame motion picture stars|motion pictures star]] on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in 1960. Her star is located at 6307 Hollywood Boulevard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/theda-bara|title=Theda Bara|website=Hollywood Walk of Fame|publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce|access-date=September 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe is one of the more famous completely silent stars\u2014she never appeared in a sound film, lost or otherwise. A 1937 fire at Fox's nitrate film storage vaults in New Jersey destroyed most of that studio's silent films. Bara made more than 40 films between 1914 and 1926, but complete prints of only six still exist: ''[[The Stain (film)|The Stain]]'' (1914), ''[[A Fool There Was (1915 film)|A Fool There Was]]'' (1915), ''[[East Lynne (1916 film)|East Lynne]]'' (1916), ''[[The Unchastened Woman]]'' (1925), and two short comedies for [[Hal Roach]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nIn addition to these, a few of her films remain in fragments, including ''Cleopatra'' (just a few seconds of footage), a clip thought to be from ''The Soul of Buddha'', and a few other unidentified clips featured in the documentary ''Theda Bara et William Fox'' (2001). Most of the clips can be seen in the documentary ''The Woman with the Hungry Eyes'' (2006). As to vamping, critics stated that her portrayal of calculating, cold-hearted women was morally instructive to men. Bara responded by saying \"I will continue doing vampires as long as people sin.\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Sexy Origins and Intimate Things: The Rites and Rituals of Straights, Gays, Bi's, Drags, Trans, Virgins, and Others|last=Panati|first=Charles|author-link=Charles Panati|year=1998|publisher=Penguin Books|page=295}}</ref> Additional footage has been found which shows her behind the scenes on a picture.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://ngataonga.org.nz/collections/catalogue/catalogue-item?record_id=79334|title=Fads and Fashion of 1900 [& Other Newsreels]|medium=film|year=1905|publisher=Fun Film|minutes=8|via=[[Ng\u0101 Taonga Sound & Vision]]}}</ref> While the hairstyle has led some to theorize that this may be from ''[[The Lure of Ambition]]'', this has not been confirmed.\n\nIn 1994, she was honored with her image on a [[List of people on the postage stamps of the United States|U.S. postage stamp]] designed by caricaturist [[Al Hirschfeld]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=March 26, 1994|title=Hirschfeld draws silent screen stars stamps|journal=Stamps|volume=246|issue=13|pages=353|id={{ProQuest|220978182}}}}</ref> The Fort Lee Film Commission dedicated Main Street and Linwood Avenue in [[Fort Lee, New Jersey]] as \"Theda Bara Way\" in May 2006 to honor Bara, who made many of her films at the Fox Studio on Linwood and Main.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A421124059|title=A Star in the Era Before Hollywood|last=Page|first=Jeffery|date=July 9, 2015|work=The Record|access-date=August 21, 2019|via=Gale Onefile:News}}</ref>\n\nOver a period of several years, filmmaker and film historian Phillip Dye reconstructed ''Cleopatra'' on video. Titled ''Lost Cleopatra'', the full-length feature was created by editing together production-still picture montages combined with the surviving film clip. The script was based on the original scenario with modifications derived from research into censorship reports, reviews of the film, and synopses from period magazines.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Lost Cleopatra|url=http://www.lostcleopatra.com|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> Dye screened the film at the [[Hollywood Heritage Museum]] on February 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ziemba|first=Christine N.|website=LAist|date=February 6, 2017|url=http://laist.com/2017/02/06/20_of_the_coolest_events_happening_2.php|title=Twenty Of The Coolest Events Happening in L.A. This Week in Arts & Entertainment|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501083710/http://laist.com/2017/02/06/20_of_the_coolest_events_happening_2.php|archive-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Romeo and juliet1916.jpg|thumb|upright|From ''[[Romeo and Juliet (1916 Fox film)|Romeo and Juliet]]'' (1916); standing, L-R: Helen Tracy (Lady Capulet), [[Alice Gale]] (Nurse), and Edward Holt (Capulet); seated: Bara as Juliet]]\n[[File:Alan Roscoe-Theda Bara in Camille.jpg|thumb|upright|Bara with [[Alan Roscoe]] in ''[[Camille (1917 film)|Camille]]'' (1917)]]\n[[File:ThedaBara-Cleopatra.jpg|thumb|upright|Bara in ''Cleopatra'' (1917)]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1914\n| ''[[The Stain (film)|The Stain]]''\n| Gang moll\n| Credited as Theodosia Goodman\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[A Fool There Was (1915 film)|A Fool There Was]]''\n| The Vampire\n|\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[The Kreutzer Sonata (1915 film)|The Kreutzer Sonata]]''\n| Celia Friedlander\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[The Clemenceau Case]]''\n| Iza\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[The Devil's Daughter (1915 film)|The Devil's Daughter]]''\n| Gioconda Dianti\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[Lady Audley's Secret (1915 film)|Lady Audley's Secret]]''\n| Helen Talboys\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[The Two Orphans (1915 film)|The Two Orphans]]''\n| Henriette\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[Sin (1915 film)|Sin]]''\n| Rosa\n| Lost film\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[Carmen (1915 Raoul Walsh film)|Carmen]]''\n