{"title_page": "The Boswell Sisters", "text_new": "{{short description|Singing trio popular during the Jazz Age}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = The Boswell Sisters\n| image               = File: Boswell Sisters 1931.jpg\n| caption             = From left: \"Vet\", Connie and Martha in 1931\n| image_size          =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = '''Martha''': {{birth date|1905|6|09|}}<br />'''Connie''': {{birth date|1907|12|03|}}<br />'''Helvetia''': {{birth date|1911|5|20|}}\n| death_date          = '''Martha''': {{Death date and age|1958|7|02|1905|6|09|}}<br />'''Connie''': {{Death date and age|1976|10|11|1907|12|03|}}<br />'''Helvetia''': {{Death date and age|1988|11|12|1911|5|20|}}\n| origin              = [[New Orleans]], United States\n| genre               = [[Vocal jazz]]\n| years_active        = 1925\u20131936\n| label               = [[Victor Talking Machine Company|Victor]], [[Okeh Records|Okeh]], [[Brunswick Records|Brunswick]], [[Decca Records|Decca]], Columbia\n| website             = {{URL|bozzies.com}}\n| past_members        = [[Martha Boswell]]<br />[[Connie Boswell]]<br />[[Helvetia Boswell]]\n}}\n'''The Boswell Sisters''' were an American [[close harmony]] singing trio of the [[jazz]] and [[Swing music|swing]] eras, consisting of three sisters: '''[[Martha Boswell]]''' (June 9, 1905 \u2013 July 2, 1958), '''[[Connee Boswell]]''' (original name Connie, December 3, 1907 \u2013 October 11, 1976), and '''[[Helvetia \"Vet\" Boswell]]''' (May 20, 1911 \u2013 November 12, 1988). Hailing from [[uptown New Orleans]], the group was noted for their intricate harmonies and rhythmic experimentation. They attained national prominence in the United States in the 1930s during the twilight years of the [[Jazz Age]] and the onset of the [[Great Depression]].{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=297}} \n\nWhen the trio formally split in 1936, Connie continued as a solo vocalist in [[radio]], [[film]], and later [[television]] for an additional quarter of a century.{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=297}} The trio's \"unique singing style and ground-breaking arrangements fused 'blackness' and 'whiteness' in music,\" and their collaborations with \"the preeminent white swing musicians of their day\u2014the [[Dorsey Brothers]], [[Glenn Miller]], [[Benny Goodman]], [[Artie Shaw]]\u2014had a profound effect on the development of the big band sound in the 1930s.\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=297}} When assessing their legacy, scholars claim the Boswell Sisters \"made 'real' jazz commercially viable, destigmatizing the music and opening its appreciation to the wider American public.\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=298}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\n[[Image:UptownCampStBoswellSistersHouse.jpg|left|thumb|House on Camp Street in [[uptown New Orleans]] where the Boswell Sisters grew up.]]\nMartha and Connie{{efn|name=Connee}} were born in [[Kansas City, Missouri]]. Helvetia was born in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. Born to a former vaudevillian, Clyde \"A. C.\" Boswell,{{sfn|Titus|2014|pp=22\u201323}} and his music-loving wife, Meldania, the sisters\u2014along with their 14-year-old brother Clyde Jr. (\"Clydie\")\u2014landed in New Orleans as children, in 1914.{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=32}} The sisters were raised in a middle-class family at 3937 Camp Street in [[uptown New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]].{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=33}} \n\nMartha, Connie, and Vet studied classical piano, cello, and violin, respectively, under the tutelage of [[Tulane University]] professor Otto Finck.{{sfn|Register|1918}}{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=40}} They performed their classical repertoire in local recitals, often as a trio, but the city's jazz scene swiftly won them over, personally and professionally. \"We studied classical music . . . and were being prepared for the stage and a concert tour throughout the United States, but the saxophone got us,\" Martha said in a 1925 interview with the ''Shreveport Times''.{{sfn|Shreveport Times|1925}}\n\nIn addition to providing the young Boswells with formal, classical musical education, Meldania Boswell took her children regularly to see the leading African\u2013American performers of the day at the [[Lyric Theatre (Kansas City, Missouri)|Lyric Theatre]].{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=47}} There, young Connie heard [[Mamie Smith]], whose \"[[Crazy Blues]]\" (1920), the first blues record performed by an African American, was a hit. Connie would later imitate Smith's style on the Boswells' first record, \"I'm Gonna Cry (Cryin' Blues),\" before settling into her own vocal style.{{sfn|Manilla|2006}}{{sfn|Sampson|1980|p=1431}} In interviews, the sisters recalled driving around New Orleans listening for new and interesting sounds, which they often found outside African\u2013American churches and barrooms.\n\nAs their older brother Clydie began breaking away from classical music to study jazz, he introduced his sisters to the new syncopated style and to many of the young jazz players in New Orleans.{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=47}} [[Leon Roppolo]] (clarinet, guitar), [[Monk Hazel]] (drums, cornet), Pinky Vidacovich (clarinet, saxophone), [[Nappy Lamare]] (guitar, banjo), [[Ray Bauduc]] (tuba, vocals), Dan LeBlanc (tuba), [[Leon Prima]] (trumpet), [[Louis Prima]] (trumpet, vocals), [[Wingy Manone]] (trumpet, vocals), [[Al Gallodoro]] (clarinet, saxophone), [[Chink Martin]] (bass, tuba, guitar), [[Santo Pecora]] (trombone), [[Raymond Burke (clarinetist)|Raymond Burke]] (clarinet, saxophone), and [[Tony Parenti]] (clarinet, saxophone) were regular guests at the Boswell home. The sisters were particularly influenced by the cornetist [[Emmett Hardy|Emmett Louis Hardy]], another friend of Clydie's, whose well-documented talent and skill helped shape the sisters' knowledge of jazz harmony, syncopation, and improvisation. Hardy and Clydie both died young and unrecorded, Hardy of [[tuberculosis]] at age 22 and Clydie of [[flu]]-related complications at 18.\n\nAfter becoming interested in jazz, Vet took up the banjo and Connie the saxophone. Martha continued playing the piano but focused on the rhythms and idioms of [[ragtime]] and [[Dixieland|hot jazz]].\n\n== Career ==\n=== New Orleans ===\n[[Image:Boswell Sisters 1932.jpg|thumb|right|The Boswell Sisters in March 1932. From top: \"Vet,\" Martha, and Connie.]]\nThe sisters came to be well known in New Orleans while still in their early teens, making appearances in local theaters and on the emerging medium of [[radio]].{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=301}} By the early 1920s,{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=301}} they were performing regularly at local [[vaudeville]] theaters, with an act that combined classical, semi-classical, and jazz styles\u2014though, as their popularity increased, the classics faded into the background.\n\nThe sisters performed as they would for virtually their entire career: Martha and Connie seated at the piano, with Vet close behind. This arrangement served to disguise Connie's inability to walk, a condition whose source has never been fully confirmed. A childhood bout with [[polio]]{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=318}} and a go-cart accident are the two main hypotheses, and Connie backed up both of them in various media sources. One theory holds that Meldania crafted the go-cart accident story in order to spare her daughter the stigma attached to the disease.{{sfn|Vitty|2012}}\n\n=== West Coast ===\nIn 1925 they made their first record for the [[Victor Talking Machine Company|Victor Records]]. After touring with a vaudeville company through [[Arkansas]], [[Texas]], and [[Oklahoma]], the sisters arrived in [[Los Angeles]] in October 1929, mere weeks after the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|stock market crash]] which marked the beginning of the [[Great Depression]].{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=301}} They appeared on radio programs, recorded music for films, and undertook several recordings for [[OKeh Records]], recorded in Los Angeles in 1930. However, the unique approach of the trio to reworking melodies and their improvisational style did not garner universal acclamation.{{sfn|Stras|2009|pp=301\u2013302}} \n\nIn their inaugural year of radio broadcasting in California, \"station employers received letters of opprobrium from outraged listeners voicing disapproval of the sisters' new and unusual arranging and singing styles.{{sfn|Stras|2009|pp=301\u2013302}} One letter stated: \"Why don't you choke those Boswell Sisters? How wonderful it would be if they sang just one song like it was written. Really when they get through murdering it, one can never recognize the original.\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=301}} Another outraged letter from an angry listener read: \"Please get those terrible Boswell Sisters off the station! You can't follow the melody and the beat is going too rapidly. And to me they sound like savage chanters!\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=320}}\n\n=== East Coast ===\nAfter relocating to [[New York City]] in 1930, the Boswell Sisters soon attained national attention and began making national radio broadcasts. The trio had a program on [[CBS]] from 1931 to 1933.{{sfn|Dunning|1998|p=110}} They soon signed a contract with [[Brunswick Records]] and made recordings from 1931 to 1935 under the aegis of producer [[Jack Kapp]].{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=302}} These Brunswick recordings are widely regarded as milestone recordings of vocal jazz.{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=302}} For their Brunswick recordings, \"the Boswells took greater liberties, regularly changing style, tempi, modality, lyrics, time signatures and voicings (both instrumental and vocal) to create unexpected textures and effects.\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=302}} \n\nConnee's reworkings of the melodies and rhythms of popular songs, together with [[Glenn Miller]]'s arrangements and New York jazz musicians (including the [[The Dorsey Brothers|Dorsey Brothers]], [[Benny Goodman]], [[Bunny Berigan]], [[Fulton McGrath]], [[Joe Venuti]], [[Arthur Schutt]], [[Eddie Lang]], [[Joe Tarto]], [[Mannie Klein]], [[Dick McDonough]], and [[Carl Kress]]), made these recordings unlike any others. Melodies were rearranged and slowed down, major keys were changed to minor keys (sometimes in mid-song), and unexpected rhythmic changes were par for the course. They were among the few performers who were allowed to make changes to current popular tunes since, during this era, music publishers and record companies pressured performers not to alter current popular song arrangements.{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=302}} Connee also recorded a series of more conventional solo records for Brunswick during the same period.\n\n=== Popular success ===\nThe Boswell Sisters soon appeared in films during this time. They sang the lively \"Shout, Sister, Shout\" (1931), written by [[Clarence Williams (musician)|Clarence Williams]], in the 1932 film ''[[The Big Broadcast]]'', which featured [[Bing Crosby]] and [[Cab Calloway]].{{efn|name=Boardwalk Empire|The song was also featured in the television show ''[[Boardwalk Empire]]'', Season 5 Episode 5.}} The song\u2014one of the sisters' signature tunes\u2014was described in a November 2011 issue of the music magazine ''Mojo'' as \"by no means as archaic as its age.\" They sang their 1934 song \"Rock and Roll\" in the film ''[[Transatlantic Merry-Go-Round]]'', bringing with them an early use of the phrase ''rock 'n' roll'', referring in the song to \"the rolling rocking rhythm of the sea\". \n\nThe Boswell Sisters chalked up 20 hits during the 1930s, including the number-one record \"The Object of My Affection\" (1935). (Of special note is their involvement in a handful of 12\" medley/concert recordings made by [[Red Nichols]], [[Victor Young]] and [[Don Redman]] and their 1934 recording of \"[[Darktown Strutters' Ball]]\", which was issued only in Australia.) They also completed two successful tours of Europe, appeared on the inaugural television broadcast of [[CBS]], and performed on ''Hello, Europe'', the first internationally broadcast radio program.\n\nThe Boswell Sisters were among radio's earliest stars, making them one of the first hit acts of the mass-entertainment age. In 1934, the Sisters appeared 13 times on the [[Bing Crosby Entertains]] radio show on CBS. They were featured in fan magazines, and their likenesses were used in advertisements for beauty and household products.{{sfn|Cave|Titus|2014}} During the early 1930s the Boswell Sisters, [[Three X Sisters]], and [[Pickens Sisters]] were the talk of early radio female harmonizing. The [[Andrews Sisters]] started out as imitators of the Boswell Sisters.{{sfn|Berkvist|2013}} Young [[Ella Fitzgerald]] loved the Boswell Sisters and in particular idolized Connee, after whose singing style she patterned her own.{{sfn|Nicholson|2014|pp=10\u201312}}\n\nIn 1936, the group signed to Decca, but after just three records they broke up. The last recording was February 12, 1936. Approximately one month earlier, Martha Boswell had married Major [[George Lloyd (RAF officer)|George L. Lloyd]] of Britain's [[Royal Air Force]]. Connie served as her sister's only attendant at the wedding and [[Harold J. Warner]] served as their best man.{{sfn|New York Times|1936}} Lloyd was the managing director of the Aero Insurance Underwriters in New York.{{sfn|New York Times|1936}} He was a [[Company rule in Rhodesia|Rhodesian]]-born flying ace of [[the Great War]], credited with [[List of World War I aces credited with 8 victories|eight aerial victories]].{{sfn|Aerodrome|2016}} Connie Boswell continued to have a successful solo career as a singer for Decca. She changed{{efn|name=Connee|{{harvnb|Stras|2009|p=318}}: \"Connie changed the spelling of her name to 'Connee' a few years after embarking on her solo career; various reasons have been put forward for this change, including that she found it difficult and tiring to dot the 'i' when signing autographs, as her right hand and arm were weakened by [[polio]]. Family sources maintain that her sister Martha persuaded her to make the change 'for good luck'.\"}} the spelling of her name from Connie to Connee in the 1940s, reputedly because it made it easier to sign autographs.{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=318}} When she tried to become involved with the overseas [[USO]] tours during [[World War II]], she was not granted permission to travel overseas because of her disability.\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[Image:The Boswell Sisters - What's On the Air, January 1931.jpg|thumb|right|The trio in 1931.]]\nLater groups such as the Pfister Sisters, the [[the Stolen Sweets|Stolen Sweets]], Boswellmania, the [[Puppini Sisters]], YazooZazz, the Spanish group O Sister!, the Italian trio [[Sorelle Marinetti]], and the Israeli band the Hazelnuts, imitated the sisters' recordings. Canada's Company B Jazz Band includes many Boswell Sisters arrangements in its repertoire and even created a set saluting the Boswells' appearance in ''Transatlantic Merry-Go-Round'' for the cover of their second album, ''Rock & Roll''. [[The Ditty Bops]] have covered Boswell Sisters songs in concert. Caffeine Trio from Brazil also claims to have been influenced by them. There is also an Australian group, the Boswell Project, based in [[Adelaide, South Australia]]. A London harmony trio, The Haywood Sisters, have also recorded some Boswell Sisters hits and are greatly influenced by their style.\n\nIn 2001, ''The Boswell Sisters'', a major musical based on their lives, was produced at the Old Globe Theatre in [[San Diego, California]]. The play starred Michelle Duffy, Elizabeth Ward Land, and [[Amy Pietz]] and was produced by the same team that produced ''[[Forever Plaid]]''.  The show was a hit with audiences and a critical success, but failed to be picked up for a much hoped-for Broadway run.\n\nThe Boswell Sisters were inducted into the [[Vocal Group Hall of Fame]] in 1998. At a ceremony covered by the Pfister Sisters, the Boswells were inducted into the [[Louisiana Music Hall of Fame]] in 2008.\n\nIn 2014, Vet's daughter and granddaughter published ''The Boswell Legacy'', the first comprehensive book on the life and times of the influential trio.{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=33}}\n\n== Hit singles ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Single\n!colspan=\"1\"|Chart positions\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n!width=\"25\"|[[Billboard Hot 100|US]]{{sfn|Whitburn|1986}}{{efn|name=Chart Note|[[Joel Whitburn]]'s methodology for recreating pre-1940s chart positions has been\ncriticized by scholars. As such, this chart should not be taken as definitive.{{sfn|Songbook|2015}}}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|1931\n|\"When I Take My Sugar to Tea\"\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n|\"Roll On, Mississippi, Roll On\"\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|\"[[I Found a Million Dollar Baby (in a Five and Ten Cent Store)|I Found a Million Dollar Baby]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|\"It's the Girl\"\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|\"(With You on My Mind I Find) I Can't Write the Words\"\n|align=\"center\"|20\n|-\n|\"Gems from ''George White's Scandals''\"\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|\"An Evening in Caroline\"\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1932\n|\"Was That the Human Thing to Do?\"\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|\"Stop the Sun, Stop the Moon (My Man's Gone)\"\n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n|\"[[Between the Devil and the Deep Blue Sea (song)|Between the Devil and the Deep Blue Sea]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1934\n|\"Coffee in the Morning (Kisses in the Night)\"\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|-\n|\"[[You Oughta Be in Pictures]] (My Star of Stars)\"\n|align=\"center\"|17\n|-\n|\"Rock and Roll\"\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|1935\n|\"The Object of My Affection\"\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|\"[[Dinah (song)|Dinah]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|\"[[Alexander's Ragtime Band]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|\"[[Saint Louis Blues (song)|St. Louis Blues]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|15\n|-\n|\"[[Cheek to Cheek]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|1936\n|\"[[I'm Gonna Sit Right Down and Write Myself a Letter]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|1938\n|\"[[Alexander's Ragtime Band]]\" <small>(re-issue)</small>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n'''<big>Book sources</big>'''\n* {{Cite sign|last1=Cave|first1=Mark|last2=Titus|first2=Kyla|title=Shout, Sister, Shout! The Boswell Sisters of New Orleans |year=2014 |type=Text panel for the 2014 exhibition |publisher=The Historic New Orleans Collection |location=[[New Orleans]]|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220093006/http://www.hnoc.org/boswellsisters/|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dunning|first=John|title=On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio|url=https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn |url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn/page/110 110]|quote=The Boswell Sisters, singing trio.|year=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-507678-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Nicholson|first=Stuart|title=Ella Fitzgerald: A Biography of the First Lady of Jazz, Updated Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M1QSBAAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-13-678814-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite magazine |date=October 1, 1918|title=The Register: Bulletin of the Tulane University of Louisiana 1917\u20131918|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HisXAAAAYAAJ|series=19|language=English|location=New Orleans|publisher=Tulane University|publication-date=October 1, 1918|issue=13|page=186, 178|access-date=November 11, 2018|df=mdy-all|ref={{harvid|Register|1918}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sampson|first=Henry|title=Blacks in Blackface: A Source Book on Early Black Musical Shows|year=1980|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Metuchen, New Jersey|isbn=978-0-8108-1318-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/blacksinblackfac0000samp|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Titus|first=Kyla|editor-last=Von Schilling|editor-first=James|title=Boswell Legacy: The Story of the Boswell Sisters of New Orleans and the New Music They Gave to the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OsP5oQEACAAJ|year=2014|publisher=CreateSpace|isbn=978-1-5023-5091-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|author-link=Joel Whitburn|title=Pop Memories: 1890\u20131954|year=1986|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit|url-access=registration|publisher=Record Research|isbn=978-0-8982-0083-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal | last = Stras | first = Laurie | title = Sing a Song of Difference: Connie Boswell and a Discourse of Disability in Jazz | year = 2009 | journal = Popular Music | volume = 28 | issue = 3 | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | pages = 297-322 | doi = 10.1017/S0261143009990080 | ref = harv| doi-access = free }}\n\n<br><big>'''Online sources'''</big>\n* {{cite news|last=Berkvist|first=Robert|date=January 30, 2013|title=Patty Andrews, Singer With Her Sisters, Is Dead at 94|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/31/arts/music/patty-andrews-singer-with-the-andrews-sisters-dies-at-94.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|page=A21|edition=National|location=New York|access-date=November 11, 2018|df=mdy-all|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news|date=January 1, 1936|title=Bridal Set For Today By Martha Boswell|url=https://nyti.ms/2z3a1Vs|work=[[The New York Times]]|page=36|location=New York|access-date=November 11, 2018|df=mdy-all|ref={{harvid|New York Times|1936}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=George Lloyd|work=The Aerodrome|year=2016|url=http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/safrica/lloyd.php|df=mdy-all|access-date=December 13, 2016|ref={{harvid|Aerodrome|2016}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Joel Whitburn Criticism: Chart Fabrication, Misrepresentation of Sources, Cherry Picking|url=https://songbook1.wordpress.com/fx/joel-whitburn-criticism-chart-fabrication-misrepresentation-of-sources-cherry-picking/|date=March 3, 2013|work=Songbook|access-date=July 15, 2015|ref={{harvid|Songbook|2015}}}}\n* {{cite episode|title=Mamie Smith and the Birth of the Blues Market|episode-link= |url=https://www.npr.org/2006/11/11/6473116/mamie-smith-and-the-birth-of-the-blues-market|access-date=November 11, 2018|series=All Things Considered|series-link= |first=Ben|last=Manilla||date=November 11, 2006|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news|date=December 12, 1925|title='Saxophones Got Us,' Three Boswells Declare, Reason for Surrendering to Jazz|url=http://bozzies.org/boz-buz-vintage-article/|work=[[The Shreveport Times]]|location=Louisiana|access-date=January 8, 2014|df=mdy-all|ref={{harvid|Shreveport Times|1925}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=The Personal Storm of Connee Boswell|last=Vitty|first=Cort|url=http://www.mwotrc.com/rr2012_02/boswell.htm|date=February 2012|website=Radio Recall|access-date=November 11, 2018|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Boswell Sisters}}\n{{Wikipedia books|The Boswell Sisters}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131210040010/http://theboswellsisters.com/index.html The Boswell Sisters Website]\n* [http://bozzies.com/ The Boswell Sisters website Bozzies.com]\n* [http://hnoc.minisisinc.com/thnoc/catalog/3/11276 Boswell Museum of Music Collection] at [https://www.hnoc.org/   The Historic New Orleans Collection]\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070312021250/http://www.vocalgroup.org/inductees/boswell_sisters.html The Boswell Sisters Vocal Group Hall of Fame Page]\n* {{IMDb name|id=1270195|name=The Boswell Sisters}}\n\n{{The Boswell Sisters}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boswell Sisters, The}}\n[[Category:Family musical groups]]\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical trios]]\n[[Category:American female jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Okeh Records artists]]\n[[Category:American girl groups]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:Victor Records artists]]\n[[Category:Vocalion Records artists]]\n[[Category:Scat singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Louisiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Singing trio popular during the Jazz Age}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = The Boswell Sisters\n| image               = File: Boswell Sisters 1931.jpg\n| caption             = From left: \"Vet\", Connie and Martha in 1931\n| image_size          =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = '''Martha''': {{birth date|1905|6|09|}}<br />'''Connie''': {{birth date|1907|12|03|}}<br />'''Helvetia''': {{birth date|1911|5|20|}}\n| death_date          = '''Martha''': {{Death date and age|1958|7|02|1905|6|09|}}<br />'''Connie''': {{Death date and age|1976|10|11|1907|12|03|}}<br />'''Helvetia''': {{Death date and age|1988|11|12|1911|5|20|}}\n| origin              = [[New Orleans]], United States\n| genre               = [[Vocal jazz]]\n| years_active        = 1925\u20131936\n| label               = [[Victor Talking Machine Company|Victor]], [[Okeh Records|Okeh]], [[Brunswick Records|Brunswick]], [[Decca Records|Decca]], Columbia\n| website             = {{URL|bozzies.com}}\n| past_members        = [[Martha Boswell]]<br />[[Connie Boswell]]<br />[[Helvetia Boswell]]\n}}\n'''The Boswell Sisters''' were an American [[close harmony]] singing trio of the [[jazz]] and [[Swing music|swing]] eras, consisting of three sisters: '''[[Martha Boswell]]''' (June 9, 1905 \u2013 July 2, 1958), '''[[Connee Boswell]]''' (original name Connie, December 3, 1907 \u2013 October 11, 1976), and '''[[Helvetia \"Vet\" Boswell]]''' (May 20, 1911 \u2013 November 12, 1988). Hailing from [[uptown New Orleans]], the group was noted for their intricate harmonies and rhythmic experimentation. They attained national prominence in the United States in the 1930s during the twilight years of the [[Jazz Age]] and the onset of the [[Great Depression]].{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=297}} \n\nWhen the trio formally split in 1936, Connie continued as a solo vocalist in [[radio]], [[film]], and later [[television]] for an additional quarter of a century.{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=297}} The trio's \"unique singing style and ground-breaking arrangements fused 'blackness' and 'whiteness' in music,\" and their collaborations with \"the preeminent white swing musicians of their day\u2014the [[Dorsey Brothers]], [[Glenn Miller]], [[Benny Goodman]], [[Artie Shaw]]\u2014had a profound effect on the development of the big band sound in the 1930s.\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=297}} When assessing their legacy, scholars claim the Boswell Sisters \"made 'real' jazz commercially viable, destigmatizing the music and opening its appreciation to the wider American public.\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=298}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\n[[Image:UptownCampStBoswellSistersHouse.jpg|left|thumb|House on Camp Street in [[uptown New Orleans]] where the Boswell Sisters grew up.]]\nMartha and Connie{{efn|name=Connee}} were born in [[Kansas City, Missouri]]. Helvetia was born in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. Born to a former vaudevillian, Clyde \"A. C.\" Boswell,{{sfn|Titus|2014|pp=22\u201323}} and his music-loving wife, Meldania, the sisters\u2014along with their 14-year-old brother Clyde Jr. (\"Clydie\")\u2014landed in New Orleans as children, in 1914.{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=32}} The sisters were raised in a middle-class family at 3937 Camp Street in [[uptown New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]].{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=33}} \n\nMartha, Connie, and Vet studied classical piano, cello, and violin, respectively, under the tutelage of [[Tulane University]] professor Otto Finck.{{sfn|Register|1918}}{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=40}} They performed their classical repertoire in local recitals, often as a trio, but the city's jazz scene swiftly won them over, personally and professionally. \"We studied classical music . . . and were being prepared for the stage and a concert tour throughout the United States, but the saxophone got us,\" Martha said in a 1925 interview with the ''Shreveport Times''.{{sfn|Shreveport Times|1925}}\n\nIn addition to providing the young Boswells with formal, classical musical education, Meldania Boswell took her children regularly to see the leading African\u2013American performers of the day at the [[Lyric Theatre (Kansas City, Missouri)|Lyric Theatre]].{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=47}} There, young Connie heard [[Mamie Smith]], whose \"[[Crazy Blues]]\" (1920), the first blues record performed by an African American, was a hit. Connie would later imitate Smith's style on the Boswells' first record, \"I'm Gonna Cry (Cryin' Blues),\" before settling into her own vocal style.{{sfn|Manilla|2006}}{{sfn|Sampson|1980|p=1431}} In interviews, the sisters recalled driving around New Orleans listening for new and interesting sounds, which they often found outside African\u2013American churches and barrooms.\n\nAs their older brother Clydie began breaking away from classical music to study jazz, he introduced his sisters to the new syncopated style and to many of the young jazz players in New Orleans.{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=47}} [[Leon Roppolo]] (clarinet, guitar), [[Monk Hazel]] (drums, cornet), Pinky Vidacovich (clarinet, saxophone), [[Nappy Lamare]] (guitar, banjo), [[Ray Bauduc]] (tuba, vocals), Dan LeBlanc (tuba), [[Leon Prima]] (trumpet), [[Louis Prima]] (trumpet, vocals), [[Wingy Manone]] (trumpet, vocals), [[Al Gallodoro]] (clarinet, saxophone), [[Chink Martin]] (bass, tuba, guitar), [[Santo Pecora]] (trombone), [[Raymond Burke (clarinetist)|Raymond Burke]] (clarinet, saxophone), and [[Tony Parenti]] (clarinet, saxophone) were regular guests at the Boswell home. The sisters were particularly influenced by the cornetist [[Emmett Hardy|Emmett Louis Hardy]], another friend of Clydie's, whose well-documented talent and skill helped shape the sisters' knowledge of jazz harmony, syncopation, and improvisation. Hardy and Clydie both died young and unrecorded, Hardy of [[tuberculosis]] at age 22 and Clydie of [[flu]]-related complications at 18.\n\nAfter becoming interested in jazz, Vet took up the banjo and Connie the saxophone. Martha continued playing the piano but focused on the rhythms and idioms of [[ragtime]] and [[Dixieland|hot jazz]].\n\n== Career ==\n=== New Orleans ===\n[[Image:Boswell Sisters 1932.jpg|thumb|right|The Boswell Sisters in March 1932. From top: \"Vet,\" Martha, and Connie.]]\nThe sisters came to be well known in New Orleans while still in their early teens, making appearances in local theaters and on the emerging medium of [[radio]].{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=301}} By the early 1920s,{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=301}} they were performing regularly at local [[vaudeville]] theaters, with an act that combined classical, semi-classical, and jazz styles\u2014though, as their popularity increased, the classics faded into the background.\n\nThe sisters performed as they would for virtually their entire career: Martha and Connie seated at the piano, with Vet close behind. This arrangement served to disguise Connie's inability to walk, a condition whose source has never been fully confirmed. A childhood bout with [[polio]]{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=318}} and a go-cart accident are the two main hypotheses, and Connie backed up both of them in various media sources. One theory holds that Meldania crafted the go-cart accident story in order to spare her daughter the stigma attached to the disease.{{sfn|Vitty|2012}}\n\n=== West Coast ===\nIn 1925 they made their first record for the [[Victor Talking Machine Company|Victor Records]]. After touring with a vaudeville company through [[Arkansas]], [[Texas]], and [[Oklahoma]], the sisters arrived in [[Los Angeles]] in October 1929, mere weeks after the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|stock market crash]] which marked the beginning of the [[Great Depression]].{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=301}} They appeared on radio programs, recorded music for films, and undertook several recordings for [[OKeh Records]], recorded in Los Angeles in 1930. However, the unique approach of the trio to reworking melodies and their improvisational style did not garner universal acclamation.{{sfn|Stras|2009|pp=301\u2013302}} \n\nIn their inaugural year of radio broadcasting in California, \"station employers received letters of opprobrium from outraged listeners voicing disapproval of the sisters' new and unusual arranging and singing styles.{{sfn|Stras|2009|pp=301\u2013302}} One letter stated: \"Why don't you choke those Boswell Sisters? How wonderful it would be if they sang just one song like it was written. Really when they get through murdering it, one can never recognize the original.\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=301}} Another outraged letter from an angry listener read: \"Please get those terrible Boswell Sisters off the station! You can't follow the melody and the beat is going too rapidly. And to me they sound like savage chanters!\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=320}}\n\n=== East Coast ===\nAfter relocating to [[New York City]] in 1930, the Boswell Sisters soon attained national attention and began making national radio broadcasts. The trio had a program on [[CBS]] from 1931 to 1933.{{sfn|Dunning|1998|p=110}} They soon signed a contract with [[Brunswick Records]] and made recordings from 1931 to 1935 under the aegis of producer [[Jack Kapp]].{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=302}} These Brunswick recordings are widely regarded as milestone recordings of vocal jazz.{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=302}} For their Brunswick recordings, \"the Boswells took greater liberties, regularly changing style, tempi, modality, lyrics, time signatures and voicings (both instrumental and vocal) to create unexpected textures and effects.\"{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=302}} \n\nConnee's reworkings of the melodies and rhythms of popular songs, together with [[Glenn Miller]]'s arrangements and New York jazz musicians (including the [[The Dorsey Brothers|Dorsey Brothers]], [[Benny Goodman]], [[Bunny Berigan]], [[Fulton McGrath]], [[Joe Venuti]], [[Arthur Schutt]], [[Eddie Lang]], [[Joe Tarto]], [[Mannie Klein]], [[Dick McDonough]], and [[Carl Kress]]), made these recordings unlike any others. Melodies were rearranged and slowed down, major keys were changed to minor keys (sometimes in mid-song), and unexpected rhythmic changes were par for the course. They were among the few performers who were allowed to make changes to current popular tunes since, during this era, music publishers and record companies pressured performers not to alter current popular song arrangements.{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=302}} Connee also recorded a series of more conventional solo records for Brunswick during the same period.\n\n=== Popular success ===\nThe Boswell Sisters soon appeared in films during this time. They sang the lively \"Shout, Sister, Shout\" (1931), written by [[Clarence Williams (musician)|Clarence Williams]], in the 1932 film ''[[The Big Broadcast]]'', which featured [[Bing Crosby]] and [[Cab Calloway]].{{efn|name=Boardwalk Empire|The song was also featured in the television show ''[[Boardwalk Empire]]'', Season 5 Episode 5.}} The song\u2014one of the sisters' signature tunes\u2014was described in a November 2011 issue of the music magazine ''Mojo'' as \"by no means as archaic as its age.\" They sang their 1934 song \"Rock and Roll\" in the film ''[[Transatlantic Merry-Go-Round]]'', bringing with them an early use of the phrase ''rock 'n' roll'', referring in the song to \"the rolling rocking rhythm of the sea\". \n\nThe Boswell Sisters chalked up 20 hits during the 1930s, including the number-one record \"The Object of My Affection\" (1935). (Of special note is their involvement in a handful of 12\" medley/concert recordings made by [[Red Nichols]], [[Victor Young]] and [[Don Redman]] and their 1934 recording of \"[[Darktown Strutters' Ball]]\", which was issued only in Australia.) They also completed two successful tours of Europe, appeared on the inaugural television broadcast of [[CBS]], and performed on ''Hello, Europe'', the first internationally broadcast radio program.\n\nThe Boswell Sisters were among radio's earliest stars, making them one of the first hit acts of the mass-entertainment age. In 1934, the Sisters appeared 13 times on the [[Bing Crosby Entertains]] radio show on CBS. They were featured in fan magazines, and their likenesses were used in advertisements for beauty and household products.{{sfn|Cave|Titus|2014}} During the early 1930s the Boswell Sisters, [[Three X Sisters]], and [[Pickens Sisters]] were the talk of early radio female harmonizing. The [[Andrews Sisters]] started out as imitators of the Boswell Sisters.{{sfn|Berkvist|2013}} Young [[Ella Fitzgerald]] loved the Boswell Sisters and in particular idolized Connee, after whose singing style she patterned her own.{{sfn|Nicholson|2014|pp=10\u201312}}\n\nIn 1936, the group signed to Decca, but after just three records they broke up. The last recording was February 12, 1936. Approximately one month earlier, Martha Boswell had married Major [[George Lloyd (RAF officer)|George L. Lloyd]] of Britain's [[Royal Air Force]]. Connie served as her sister's only attendant at the wedding and [[Harold J. Warner]] served as their best man.{{sfn|New York Times|1936}} Lloyd was the managing director of the Aero Insurance Underwriters in New York.{{sfn|New York Times|1936}} He was a [[Company rule in Rhodesia|Rhodesian]]-born flying ace of [[the Great War]], credited with [[List of World War I aces credited with 8 victories|eight aerial victories]].{{sfn|Aerodrome|2016}} Connie Boswell continued to have a successful solo career as a singer for Decca. She changed{{efn|name=Connee|{{harvnb|Stras|2009|p=318}}: \"Connie changed the spelling of her name to 'Connee' a few years after embarking on her solo career; various reasons have been put forward for this change, including that she found it difficult and tiring to dot the 'i' when signing autographs, as her right hand and arm were weakened by [[polio]]. Family sources maintain that her sister Martha persuaded her to make the change 'for good luck'.\"}} the spelling of her name from Connie to Connee in the 1940s, reputedly because it made it easier to sign autographs.{{sfn|Stras|2009|p=318}} When she tried to become involved with the overseas [[USO]] tours during [[World War II]], she was not granted permission to travel overseas because of her disability.\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[Image:The Boswell Sisters - What's On the Air, January 1931.jpg|thumb|right|The trio in 1931.]]\nLater groups such as the Pfister Sisters, the [[the Stolen Sweets|Stolen Sweets]], Boswellmania, the [[Puppini Sisters]], YazooZazz, the Spanish group O Sister!, the Italian trio [[Sorelle Marinetti]], and the Israeli band the Hazelnuts, imitated the sisters' recordings. Canada's Company B Jazz Band includes many Boswell Sisters arrangements in its repertoire and even created a set saluting the Boswells' appearance in ''Transatlantic Merry-Go-Round'' for the cover of their second album, ''Rock & Roll''. [[The Ditty Bops]] have covered Boswell Sisters songs in concert. Caffeine Trio from Brazil also claims to have been influenced by them. There is also an Australian group, the Boswell Project, based in [[Adelaide, South Australia]]. A London harmony trio, The Haywood Sisters, have also recorded some Boswell Sisters hits and are greatly influenced by their style.\n\nIn 2001, ''The Boswell Sisters'', a major musical based on their lives, was produced at the Old Globe Theatre in [[San Diego, California]]. The play starred Michelle Duffy, Elizabeth Ward Land, and [[Amy Pietz]] and was produced by the same team that produced ''[[Forever Plaid]]''.  The show was a hit with audiences and a critical success, but failed to be picked up for a much hoped-for Broadway run.\n\nThe Boswell Sisters were inducted into the [[Vocal Group Hall of Fame]] in 1998. At a ceremony covered by the Pfister Sisters, the Boswells were inducted into the [[Louisiana Music Hall of Fame]] in 2008.\n\nIn 2014, Vet's daughter and granddaughter published ''The Boswell Legacy'', the first comprehensive book on the life and times of the influential trio.{{sfn|Titus|2014|p=33}}\n\n== Hit singles ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Single\n!colspan=\"1\"|Chart positions\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n!width=\"25\"|[[Billboard Hot 100|US]]{{sfn|Whitburn|1986}}{{efn|name=Chart Note|[[Joel Whitburn]]'s methodology for recreating pre-1940s chart positions has been\ncriticized by scholars. As such, this chart should not be taken as definitive.{{sfn|Songbook|2015}}}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|1931\n|\"When I Take My Sugar to Tea\"\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n|\"Roll On, Mississippi, Roll On\"\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|\"[[I Found a Million Dollar Baby (in a Five and Ten Cent Store)|I Found a Million Dollar Baby]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|\"It's the Girl\"\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|\"(With You on My Mind I Find) I Can't Write the Words\"\n|align=\"center\"|20\n|-\n|\"Gems from ''George White's Scandals''\"\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|\"An Evening in Caroline\"\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1932\n|\"Was That the Human Thing to Do?\"\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|\"Stop the Sun, Stop the Moon (My Man's Gone)\"\n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n|\"[[Between the Devil and the Deep Blue Sea (song)|Between the Devil and the Deep Blue Sea]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1934\n|\"Coffee in the Morning (Kisses in the Night)\"\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|-\n|\"[[You Oughta Be in Pictures]] (My Star of Stars)\"\n|align=\"center\"|17\n|-\n|\"Rock and Roll\"\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|1935\n|\"The Object of My Affection\"\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|\"[[Dinah (song)|Dinah]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|\"[[Alexander's Ragtime Band]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|\"[[Saint Louis Blues (song)|St. Louis Blues]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|15\n|-\n|\"[[Cheek to Cheek]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|1936\n|\"[[I'm Gonna Sit Right Down and Write Myself a Letter]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|1938\n|\"[[Alexander's Ragtime Band]]\" <small>(re-issue)</small>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n'''<big>Book sources</big>'''\n* {{Cite sign|last1=Cave|first1=Mark|last2=Titus|first2=Kyla|title=Shout, Sister, Shout! The Boswell Sisters of New Orleans |year=2014 |type=Text panel for the 2014 exhibition |publisher=The Historic New Orleans Collection |location=[[New Orleans]]|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220093006/http://www.hnoc.org/boswellsisters/|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dunning|first=John|title=On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio|url=https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn |url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn/page/110 110]|quote=The Boswell Sisters, singing trio.|year=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-507678-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Nicholson|first=Stuart|title=Ella Fitzgerald: A Biography of the First Lady of Jazz, Updated Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M1QSBAAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-13-678814-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite magazine |date=October 1, 1918|title=The Register: Bulletin of the Tulane University of Louisiana 1917\u20131918|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HisXAAAAYAAJ|series=19|language=English|location=New Orleans|publisher=Tulane University|publication-date=October 1, 1918|issue=13|page=186, 178|access-date=November 11, 2018|df=mdy-all|ref={{harvid|Register|1918}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sampson|first=Henry|title=Blacks in Blackface: A Source Book on Early Black Musical Shows|year=1980|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Metuchen, New Jersey|isbn=978-0-8108-1318-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/blacksinblackfac0000samp|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Titus|first=Kyla|editor-last=Von Schilling|editor-first=James|title=Boswell Legacy: The Story of the Boswell Sisters of New Orleans and the New Music They Gave to the World|url=http