{"title_page": "Retail apocalypse", "text_new": "{{short description|Period in the 2010s where many North American brick and mortar retail stores have closed or struggled}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n[[File:Closed Sears store with label scar over entrance, Hudson Valley Mall, Kingston, NY.jpg|thumb|right|Entrance to former [[Sears]] store at [[Hudson Valley Mall]] in [[Ulster, New York]], closed in 2018. It had been the mall's last anchor store.]]\nThe '''retail apocalypse''' (also '''retail tsunami''')<ref name=yahoo>{{cite news |last1=Sozzi |first1=Brian |title=A tsunami of bankruptcies are about to wash away America's retail sector |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/a-tsunami-of-bankruptcies-are-about-to-wash-away-americas-retail-sector-142047677.html |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> is the closing of numerous [[economy of North America|North American]] [[brick-and-mortar]] [[retail]] stores, especially those of large chains, starting around 2010 and continuing onward.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.businessinsider.com/store-closures-in-2018-will-eclipse-2017-2018-1 |title=A tsunami of store closings is about to hit the US \u2014 and it's expected to eclipse the retail carnage of 2017 |last=Peterson |first=Hayley |date=January 1, 2018 |website= businessinsider.com |access-date= January 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"atlantic\" /> \nIn 2019, US retailers announced 9,302 store closings, a 59% jump from 2018, and the highest number since tracking the data began in 2012.<ref name=\"closing 28\">[https://amp.cnn.com/cnn/2020/01/08/business/macys-store-closures/index.html Macy's is closing 28 stores and a Bloomingdale's store], Jordan Valinsky, [[CNN]] Business, January 8, 2020</ref>\nOver 12,000 physical stores have closed due to factors including over-expansion of malls, rising rents, bankruptcies of [[leveraged buyout]]s, low quarterly profits outside holiday binge spending, delayed effects of the [[Great Recession]],<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/04/retail-meltdown-of-2017/522384/|title=What in the World Is Causing the Retail Meltdown of 2017?|first=Derek|last=Thompson|date=April 10, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2017|magazine=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref> and changes in spending habits. North American consumers have shifted their purchasing habits due to various factors, including [[experience economy|experience-spending]] versus material goods and homes, casual fashion in relaxed [[dress code]]s, as well as the rise of [[e-commerce]],<ref>[https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/companies/these-haunting-photos-of-the-retail-apocalypse-reveal-a-new-normal-in-america/ss-BByFpjX Photo slideshow of shuttered retail stores and shopping centers] ''[[Business Insider]]''</ref> mostly in the form of competition from juggernaut companies such as {{anchor|Amazon effect}}[[Amazon.com]] and [[Walmart]]. A further late 2017 ''[[Business Insider]]'' report by Kate Taylor dubbed this phenomenon the \"Amazon effect,\" and calculated that [[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]] was generating greater than 50% of the growth of retail sales.<ref name=\"business-insider-amazon-effect-1nov2017\">{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=One statistic shows how much Amazon could dominate the future of retail |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/retail-apocalypse-amazon-accounts-for-half-of-all-retail-growth-2017-11 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |publisher=[[Business Insider]] |date=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2020, the rash of bankruptcies and store closings is expected to greatly intensify due to the [[Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], with most retail stores closed (other than those selling food or hardware) and no reopening date set in most U.S. states. Existing apparel stock will have to be sold at deep discounts at reopening. [[Yahoo! Finance]] referred to a \"retail tsunami\" about to happen, with [[Neiman Marcus]] set to file for bankruptcy and the future of [[J.C. Penney]] in particular, in question. <ref name=yahoo/>\n\nThe most productive retailers in the US during the retail apocalypse are the discount superstores [[Walmart]] and [[Target Corporation|Target]], the low-cost \"[[fast-fashion]]\" brands (e.g., [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]], [[Uniqlo]], [[Cotton On]], and [[H&M]]), off-price department stores ([[Ross Stores]] and DD's Discounts, [[Marshalls]] and [[Burlington (department store)|Burlington]]) and [[dollar stores]] (e.g., [[Dollar General]] and [[Dollar Tree]]).<ref>[https://qz.com/1120552/the-retail-apocalypse-isnt-just-amazon-its-that-the-middle-class-is-disappearing/ The US middle class is disappearing, which makes dollar stores very happy] Helen Edwards & Dave Edwards, [[Qz.com]] 8 December 2017</ref>\nAt least one [[private equity firm]], [[Sycamore Partners]], has made money buying assets from brick-and-mortar chains during the retail apocalypse.<ref name=\"Made a Fortune\">{{cite news\n| last= Gottfried\n| first= Miriam \n| url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-one-investor-made-a-fortune-picking-over-the-retail-apocalypse-1521643491\n| title= How One Investor Made a Fortune Picking Over the Retail Apocalypse\n| newspaper= [[Wall Street Journal]] \n| date= March 21, 2018\n}}</ref> [[Pop-up retail]], including seasonal retailers such as [[Spirit Halloween]], operating temporarily in vacant spots after companies go out of business have become more common during the retail apocalypse.\n\nResearch from IHL Group finds that when a retailer closes a lot of stores, it says more about the individual retailer rather than the retail industry overall. In 2019, the 20 stores announcing the most closures [[Pareto principle|represent]] 75% of all closures. IHL found that for each retailer that is closing stores in 2019 more than 5 retail chains are opening stores, which is up from the 3.7 ratio in 2018. IHL also reported that the number of chains adding stores in 2019 has increased 56%, while the number of closing stores has decreased by 66% in the last year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chainstoreage.com/real-estate/ihl-study-five-retailers-opening-stores-for-every-retailer-closing-stores|title=IHL Study: Five retailers opening stores for every retailer closing stores|website=Chain Store Age|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref \n[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-13/retail-apocalypse-gives-more-women-a-shot-as-ceo Retail Apocalypse Gives More Women a Shot as CEO: A strong bench of female candidates is benefiting from the industry\u2019s woes] [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]], Jordyn Holman and Jeff Green, December 13, 2019</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe term \"retail apocalypse\" began gaining widespread usage in 2017 following multiple announcements from many major retailers of plans to either discontinue or greatly scale back a retail presence, including companies such as [[H.H. Gregg]], [[Family Christian Stores]] and [[The Limited]] all going out of business entirely.<ref name=\"whioohioimpact\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.whio.com/business/retail-apocalypse-500-stores-more-close-this-year/RzTeZhnIk13YIlF0skFV3H|title=RETAIL APOCALYPSE: 3,500 stores or more to close this year|last=Driscoll|first=Kara|date=March 27, 2017|work=WHIO TV 7|accessdate=April 8, 2017|publisher=[[WHIO-TV]]}}</ref> ''[[The Atlantic]]'' described the phenomenon as \"The Great Retail Apocalypse of 2017,\" reporting nine retail bankruptcies and several apparel companies having their stock hit new lows, including that of [[Lululemon]], [[Urban Outfitters]], [[American Eagle Outfitters|American Eagle]].<ref name=\"atlantic\" /> [[Credit Suisse]], a major global financial services company, predicted that 25% of U.S. malls remaining in 2017 could close by 2022.<ref name=\"gymboree\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/06/12/childrens-apparel-chain-gymboree-files-chapter-11-bankruptcy/102772792/|title=Gymboree files bankruptcy, closing up to 450 stores|first=Nathan|last=Bomey|date=June 12, 2017|accessdate=June 12, 2017|newspaper=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n\nSince at least 2010, various economic factors have resulted in the closing of many North American stores, particularly in the [[department store]] industry. For example, [[Sears Holdings]] had more than 3,500 stores and 355,000 employees in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/12/timeline-the-rise-and-fall-of-sears.html|title=Timeline: The rise and fall of Sears|last=Schoen|first=Lauren Thomas, Dawn Kopecki, John W.|date=2018-10-12|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> By the end of 2016, Sears operated 1,430 stores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/15/sears-files-for-bankruptcy.html|title=Sears files for bankruptcy, and Eddie Lampert steps down as CEO|last=Thomas|first=Lauren Hirsch,Lauren|date=2018-10-15|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> In October 2018, Sears filed for bankruptcy and announced they would close an additional 142 of their 687 stores.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2018/10/15/sears-bankruptcy/1595399002/|title=Sears files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, to close 142 more stores|last=Jones|first=Charisse|last2=Bomey|first2=Nathan|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> At the time of filing, Sears had 68,000 employees.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe retail apocalypse has had a [[domino effect]] on suppliers; [[Hasbro]], for example, cited the loss of the [[Toys \"R\" Us]] chain as a major cause for lost revenue and layoffs the company imposed in October 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wivb.com/news/national/hasbro-points-to-toys-r-us-demise-in-announcing-layoffs/1542038375|title=Hasbro points to Toys R Us' demise in announcing layoffs|publisher=CBS News|date=October 22, 2018|accessdate=October 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2020, the rash of bankruptcies and store closings is expected to greatly intensify due to the [[Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], with [[Yahoo! Finance]] referring to a \"retail tsunami\" about to happen.<ref name=yahoo/>\n\n==Factors==\n{{Quote box\n| title = \n| quote = ... several trends\u2014including the rise of [[e-commerce]], the over-supply of malls, and the surprising effects of a restaurant renaissance\u2014have conspired to change the face of American shopping.\n| source = ''[[The Atlantic]]''<ref name=\"atlantic\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 30em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 85%\n| title_bg = \n| title_fnt = \n| salign = right\n}}\nThe main factor cited in the closing of retail stores in the retail apocalypse is the shift in consumer habits towards online shopping.<ref>Mark James, [https://target-help.com/retail-apocalypse/ Retail Apocalypse Online competition drives store closings] ''[https://target-help.com/retail-apocalypse/]'', July 16, 2018</ref> Holiday sales for e-commerce were reported as increasing by 11% for 2016 compared with 2015 by Adobe Digital Insights, with Slice Intelligence reporting an even more generous 20% increase. Comparatively, brick-and-mortar stores saw an overall increase of only 1.6%, with physical department stores experiencing a 4.8% decline.<ref name=\"practicale\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.practicalecommerce.com/articles/132707-2016-Holiday-Ecommerce-Wrap-up|title=2016 Holiday Ecommerce Wrap-up|first=Marcia|last=Kaplan|date=January 12, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2017|publisher=PracticalEcommerce}}</ref>\n\nAnother factor is an over-supply of [[shopping mall|malls]],<ref>Marc Bain, [https://qz.com/1032723/theres-much-more-empty-retail-space-in-the-us-than-in-other-countries-on-a-per-capita-level/ America\u2019s vast swaths of retail space have become a burden in the age of e-commerce] [[qz.com]] July 19, 2017</ref> as the growth rate of malls between 1970 and 2015 was over twice the growth rate of the population. In 2004, [[Malcolm Gladwell]] wrote that investment in malls was artificially accelerated when the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] introduced [[accelerated depreciation]] into the tax code in 1954.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gladwell |first=Malcolm |date=March 15, 2004 |title=The Terrazzo Jungle |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2004/03/15/the-terrazzo-jungle |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=November 9, 2017 }}</ref> Despite the construction of new malls, mall visits declined by 50% between 2010\u20132013 with further declines reported in each successive year.<ref>Josh Sanburn, [http://time.com/4865957/death-and-life-shopping-mall/ Why the Death of Malls Is About More Than Shopping] ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'', July 20, 2017</ref> A third major reported factor is the \"restaurant renaissance,\" a shift in consumer spending habits for their disposable cash from material purchases such as clothing towards [[restaurant|dining out]] and [[travel]].<ref name=\"atlantic\" />\n\nAnother cited factor is the \"[[Middle-class squeeze|death]] of the [[American middle class]],\" resulting in large-scale closures of retailers such as [[Macy's]] and [[Sears]], which traditionally relied on spending from this market segment.<ref name=\"middleclass\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/amazon-and-walmart-confirm-the-death-of-the-middle-class-2017-6|title=Amazon's and Walmart's latest moves confirm the death of the middle class as we know it|first=Hayley|last=Peterson|date=June 6, 2017|accessdate=June 6, 2017|website=[[Business Insider]]}}</ref> Particularly in rural areas, [[variety store]]s such as [[Dollar General]], once thought to be unaffected by the apocalypse since they have continued growing rapidly, are now perceived as being at best a symptom of the phenomenon, and at worst a direct cause of rural, independent retailers collapsing, unable to compete with the lower margins that national chains can sustain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/19/business/dollar-general-opposition/index.html|title=Dollar stores are facing backlash across America|last=Business|first=Nathaniel Meyersohn, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Misra |first=Tanvi |date=December 20, 2018 |title=The Dollar Store Backlash Has Begun |url=https://www.citylab.com/equity/2018/12/closest-grocery-store-to-me-dollar-store-food-desert-bargain/577777/ |work=[[CityLab (web magazine)|CityLab]] |accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe final factor in poor brick-and-mortar sales performance is a combination of poor retail management coupled with an overcritical eye towards quarterly dividends: a lack of accurate inventory control creates both underperforming and out-of-stock merchandise, causing a poor shopping experience for customers in order to optimize short-term balance sheets,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paularosenblum/2014/04/15/walmarts-out-of-stock-problem-only-half-the-story/#1fb788873696|title=Walmart's Out Of Stock Problem: Only Half The Story?|last=Rosenblum|first=Paula|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref> the latter of which also influences the desire to understaff retail stores in order to keep claimed profits high.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsrresearch.com/research/the-walmart-out-of-stock-problem-lessons-learned|title=The Walmart Out-of-Stock Problem: Lessons Learned|website=www.rsrresearch.com|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref> Furthermore, many long-standing chain retailers are [[corporate debt bubble|overloaded with debt]], often from [[leveraged buyout]]s from [[private equity]] firms, which hinders the profitable operation of retail chains.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/147669/real-retail-killer|title=The Real Retail Killer|work=The New Republic|access-date=2018-11-27|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/brick-and-mortar-retail-private-equity-debt-financing-lbo-2017-8?international=true&r=US&IR=T|title=The retail apocalypse is being fueled by private equity firms adding to debt loads|work=Business Insider|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n\n==Affected retailers==\n{{main|List of retailers affected by the retail apocalypse}}\n[[Sears Holdings]] filed for bankruptcy protection in October 2018 and planned to close about 142 of its 700 stores.\n\n[[Borders Books]] closed all stores and [[Chapter 7, Title 11, United States Code|filed for bankruptcy]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ovide|first=Shira|title=Bookstore Chain Borders Is Dead|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/deals/2011/07/18/its-almost-official-borders-is-dead|accessdate=July 28, 2011|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=July 18, 2011}}</ref> Rival bookseller [[Barnes & Noble]] acquired Borders' trademarks and customer list.\n[[File:Babies \"R\" Us - Manchester, Connecticut.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Toys \"R\" Us]] closed all its US stores in June 2018]]\n[[Toys \"R\" Us]] filed for bankruptcy<ref>[https://finance.yahoo.com/news/toys-r-us-just-beginning-retail-defaults-2018-182915327.html Toys \"R\" Us Just The Beginning of Retail Defaults in 2018] Krystal Hu, [[Yahoo! Finance]], March 15, 2018</ref> and closed all its US stores in June 2018.<ref>Brad Tuttle, [http://time.com/money/4931640/toys-r-us-sales-bankruptcy-debt/ Up Next in the Retail Apocalypse: Toys R Us?] [[Time.com]] September 7, 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/29/toys-r-us-closing-sales-stores-retail-toys.html Toys R Us closing its stores] Darren Geeter, [[CNBC]], 29 June 2018</ref>\n\n[[Bloomingdale's]] in 2012 announced it would close four stores, including at the [[Mall of America]] in [[Bloomington, Minnesota]]. Additionally, a home store at [[Oakbrook Center]] in [[Oak Brook, Illinois]] and full-line stores in [[Perimeter Mall]] in [[Dunwoody, Georgia]] and at [[White Flint Mall]] in [[North Bethesda, Maryland]] have closed their doors. On January 3, 2013, Bloomingdale's announced that they would close the [[Las Vegas]] Home store at [[Fashion Show Mall]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Zackie Binkes |url=http://www.vegasinc.com/news/2013/jan/03/bloomingdales-closing-store-fashion-show-mall/ |title=Bloomingdale's store closing at Fashion Show mall |publisher=Vegas Inc |date= 2013-01-03|accessdate=February 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Guess (clothing)|GUESS?]] closed 60 stores in 2017 and was expected to close more than 100 stores in 2018,<ref name=\"life support\" /> leaving roughly half of its high of 400 stores.<ref name=\"life support\">[https://www.forbes.com/sites/pamdanziger/2018/01/14/9-fashion-retailers-on-life-support/ 9 fashion retailers on life support] Pamela N. Danziger, [[Forbes.com]] 2018/01/14</ref>\n\n[[J. C. Penney]] announced in February 2017 that it would close 138 stores in 2017. Liquidation sales began on May 22, and stores closed by July 31.<ref name=\"penneydelay\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.whio.com/business/penney-postponing-store-closures/s7JjaCX6utJWzrJeZwAbFP/|title=JC Penney postponing store closures|first=Kara|last=Driscoll|date=April 13, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2017|publisher=WHIO-TV}}</ref> Another 8 stores and a distribution center closed in 2018. J. C. Penney announced plans to close a total of 30 stores in 2019.<ref>[https://amp.usatoday.com/amp/3013368002 J.C. Penney to close 24 more stores: Sales fall as department stores struggle] NATHAN BOMEY, ''[[USA TODAY]]'', 28 February 2019</ref>\n\n[[J. Crew]] closed 61 stores in 2017 and closed additional stores in the first quarter of 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lehighvalleylive.com/lehigh-county/index.ssf/2018/03/j_crew_ann_taylor_out_at_lehig.html |title=J. Crew, Ann Taylor out at Lehigh Valley Mall |last=Cassi |first=Sarah |date=March 15, 2018 |website=lehighvalleylive.com |access-date=March 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Payless ShoeSource]] plans to close all its 2,000 stores in the US and Canada,<ref>[https://www.today.com/today/amp/tdna148992 Payless ShoeSource plans to liquidate and close all U.S. stores] ''TODAY'', Ronnie Koenig, February 16, 2019</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4975274/payless-shoesource-stores-closing-canada/|title=Payless to close all 248 Canadian stores, liquidation sales expected {{!}} Globalnews.ca|date=2019-02-19|website=globalnews.ca|language=en|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref> and is going out of business.\n\n[[Topshop]] is closing all its US stores as its parent company, [[Arcadia Group]], seeks to restructure after filing for bankruptcy.<ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/24/business/topshop-topman-store-closing/index.html Topshop is closing all US stores] [[CNN]], Nathaniel Meyersohn, May 24, 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.afr.com/business/retail/clothing-and-accessories/topshop-pulls-out-of-the-us-australian-stores-in-doubt-20190603-p51u36 Topshop pulls out of the US, last Australian store in doubt] ''[[Australian Financial Review]]'', Sue Mitchell, June 4, 2019</ref>\n\n[[Barneys New York]] plans to close 15 stores after filing for [[Chapter 11 bankruptcy]]. <ref>[https://wwd.com/business-news/financial/barneys-new-york-richard-perry-bankruptcy-1203225430/ Barneys Files for Chapter 11 Bankruptcy Protection: The luxe department store has been struggling with higher rent and a changing consumer] ''[[Women's Wear Daily]]'', Evan Clark and Sindhu Sundar, August 6, 2019</ref><ref>[https://amp.usatoday.com/amp/1930050001 Barneys New York files for bankruptcy and announces 15 closing stores] KELLY TYKO, [[USA TODAY]], 6 August 2019</ref>Authentic Brands Group acquired the chain and licensed it to [[Saks Fifth Avenue]], and close the last seven stores. \n\n[[Forever 21]] filed for bankruptcy in October 2019 and said it would close up to 178 in the US and 350 stores globally.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/forever-21-bankruptcy-when-to-spend-gift-cards-2019-10 Forever 21 has filed for bankruptcy] ''[[Business Insider]]'', Shoshy Ciment, October 3, 2019\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/29/business/forever-21-bankruptcy/index.html|title=Forever 21 files for bankruptcy, intends to close up to 178 of its US stores.|last=Business|first=Nathaniel Meyersohn and Chris Isidore, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n[[A.C. Moore]] announced in November 2019 that all 145 locations will be closed.<ref>[https://nypost.com/2019/11/26/ac-moore-going-out-of-business-will-close-all-145-stores/ A C Moore going out of business] ''New York Post'', 2019/11/26</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Macy's]] announced it would close 125 department stores over the next three years,<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/04/macys-to-close-125-stores-sees-480-million-in-restructuring-costs-to-2000-corporate-jobs.html Macy\u2019s to close 125 stores, cut 2,000 corporate jobs, in hunt for growth] [[CNBC]], Lauren Thomas, February 4, 2020 </ref> following a sales decline of 3.9% at stores open for at least a year, which Macy's CEO Jeff Gennette said was \"steeper than we expected.\"<ref name=\"closing 28\" />\n[[File:Macy's\u00ae Hilldale - panoramio.jpg|right|thumb|300px| [[Macy's]] announced it would close 125 department stores 2020-2023]]\n\n[[Express, Inc.]] announced 31 store closures in January 2020; and 35 more stores will close by the end of January 2021. All other Express stores will close by 2022.<ref>[https://amp.usatoday.com/amp/4567461002 Express is closing 31 stores] KELLY TYKO, [[USA TODAY]], 23 January 2020</ref>\n\n[[Pier 1 Imports]] filed [[Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] proceedings in the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in February 2020.<ref>[https://www.newsy.com/stories/pier-1-imports-files-for-bankruptcy-protections/ Pier 1 Imports Files For Chapter 11 Protections] Briana Koeneman, ''newsy'', February 17, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 5, 2020, [[Art Van|Art Van Furniture]] announced that it would be closing all of its company-owned stores as it plans to file for [[chapter 11 bankruptcy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/money/business/2020/03/05/art-van-furniture-bankruptcy-liquidation/4951107002/|title=Art Van Furniture to close its stores, begin liquidation sales|last=Reindl|first=JC|date=2020-03-05|website=Detroit Free Press|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/05/art-van-store-closings-art-van-furniture-bankruptcy-liquidation/4962599002/?utm_source=feedblitz&utm_medium=FeedBlitzRss&utm_campaign=usatodaycommoney-topstories USA Today]</ref>\n\nOn April 19, 2020, [[Neiman Marcus]], announced it would file for bankruptcy as early as that week.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/19/business/19reuters-neimanmarcus-bankruptcy-exclusive.html]</ref>\n\n==Retailers succeeding in the apocalypse==\n[[File:Ulta Beauty Ann Arbor.JPG|thumb|right|[[Ulta Beauty]] opened 100 stores in 2018.]]\n[[File:Build-A-BearWorkshopVaughanMills.JPG|thumb|As of 2018, [[Build-A-Bear Workshop]] had expanded its physical footprint by 12% and had been profitable for four straight years.<ref>{{cite news| last= Bahler | first= Kristen| url= http://time.com/money/5216826/toys-r-us-retail-closing/| title= As Toys R' Us Closes, Only One Major Toy Store Is Thriving in the Retail Apocalypse| magazine= [[Time (magazine)|Time]]| date= March 27, 2018| accessdate=}}</ref>]]\nIn the second half of 2017 and throughout 2018, the media and analyst community began recognizing retail as an industry in transition, rather than demise. [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] said in May 2018 that 'the death of retail has been greatly exaggerated' and Telsey Advisory Group stated that 'retail is not dead' in August 2018 following news that the SPDR S&P Retail ETF had risen 13% year to date to a record high, more than double the return of the S&P 500 Index.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/31/digital-retailers-and-foreign-brands-fill-empty-us-malls.html|title=Is the retail collapse over? Shopping mall owners think so.|last=Thomas|first=Lauren|date=2018-07-31|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-05-01/e-commerce-costs-rise-just-as-commercial-real-estate-costs-fall|title=The Return of the Brick-and-Mortar Store|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, SeekingAlpha reported that 90% of purchases were still made in physical stores.<ref name=\"Wake Up\" /> SeekingAlpha noted that the top ten retailers ([[Walmart]], [[Kroger]], [[Costco]], [[Home Depot]], [[CVS Health|CVS]], [[Walgreens]], [[Amazon.com]], [[Target Corporation|Target]], [[Lowe's]] and [[Albertsons]]) are mostly brick-and-mortar operations.<ref name=\"Wake Up\">{{Cite news|url=https://seekingalpha.com/article/4184162-retail-apocalypse-wake-experience-renaissance?page=3|title=What Retail Apocalypse? Wake Up And Experience The 'Renaissance'|last=Thomas|first=Brad|date=2018-06-27|work=Seeking Alpha|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nNumerous online retailers including [[Warby Parker]], [[Untuckit]], [[Casper Sleep]], [[Away (luggage)|Away]], [[Wayfair]] and [[The RealReal]] have announced plans to open their first physical stores and expand their existing footprints in 2018 and beyond.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/31/digital-retailers-and-foreign-brands-fill-empty-us-malls.html|title=Is the retail collapse over? Shopping mall owners think so.|last=Thomas|first=Lauren|date=2018-07-31|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/casper-a-web-pioneer-to-open-200-stores-1533729600|title=Casper, a Web Pioneer, to Open 200 Stores|last=Safdar|first=Khadeeja|work=WSJ|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40575801/as-luggage-startups-drop-like-flies-away-beefs-up-with-249-jobs|title=As luggage startups drop like flies, Away beefs up with 249 jobs|date=2018-05-21|work=Fast Company|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n[[JLL (company)|JLL]] reports that digitally native brands will open 850 stores in the next five years. These retailers are finding that opening a physical store has a halo effect on web traffic: A study from the International Council of Shopping Centers shows that a new store increases traffic to that retailer's website by an average of 37% and drives up share of web traffic within that market by 27%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.retaildive.com/news/e-commerce-pure-plays-set-to-open-850-stores-in-five-years/539320/|title=Digitally native brands set to open 850 stores in 5 years|work=Retail Dive|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reports.icsc.org/thehaloeffect|title=The Halo Effect: How Bricks Impact Clicks|website=reports.icsc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-10-22/warby-parker-and-casper-are-coming-to-a-strip-mall-near-you|title=Warby Parker and Casper Are Coming to a Strip Mall Near You|website=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2014 to 2020, [[beauty supply store]] [[Ulta Beauty]] approximately doubled its number of stores, from 675 in 2014 to 1,254 retail stores across 50 states as of February 1, 2020.<ref>ir.ultabeauty.com/overview/default.aspx</ref>\n\nParticularly in rural areas, dollar stores ([[variety store]]s) such as [[Dollar General]], [[Dollar Tree]] and [[Family Dollar]] have continued growing rapidly.<ref name=dollar/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Business|History|Companies|United States}}\n*[[Dead mall]]\n*[[Economic history of the United States]]\n*[[Experience economy]]\n*[[Pop-up shop]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n; Videos:\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BBmvMpZCNJg|title=American shopping malls struggle to survive|work=[[CBS Sunday Morning]]|publisher=[[CBS]]|date=2014-03-30}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I7y1FoFqtiw|title=The rise and fall of the American shopping mall|work=[[PBS Newshour]]|publisher=[[PBS]]|date=2014-11-28}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oooVC3zfDc8|title=What America's shopping mall decline means for social space|publisher=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|date=2018-04-06}}\n\n==External links==\n*Brian Sozzi, [https://www.thestreet.com/story/14298940/1/coach-ceo-perfectly-explains-what-must-be-done-to-survive-retail-apocalypse.html Coach CEO Perfectly Explains What Must Be Done to Survive Retail Apocalypse] [[thestreet.com]] September 8, 2017\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/13/fashion/shopping-online-retail.html The Death Knell for the Bricks-and-Mortar Store? Not Yet] MATTHEW SCHNEIER, [[New York Times]], November 13, 2017\n*[http://www.newser.com/story/253582/the-mall-was-dead-except-for-the-jc-penney.html What It's Like to Work in the Last Big Store in a Dying Mall] [[Washington Post]]/Newser, Kate Seamons, January 2, 2018\n\n{{Economic history}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:2013 in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2018 in Canada]]\n[[Category:2016 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2017 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2018 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Economic history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Urban decay]]\n[[Category:Economic problems]]\n[[Category:2016 in economics]]\n[[Category:2017 in economics]]\n[[Category:2018 in economics]]\n[[Category:2019 in economics]]\n[[Category:History of retail in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Period in the 2010s where many North American brick and mortar retail stores have closed or struggled}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n[[File:Closed Sears store with label scar over entrance, Hudson Valley Mall, Kingston, NY.jpg|thumb|right|Entrance to former [[Sears]] store at [[Hudson Valley Mall]] in [[Ulster, New York]], closed in 2018. It had been the mall's last anchor store.]]\nThe '''retail apocalypse''' (also '''retail tsunami''')<ref name=yahoo>{{cite news |last1=Sozzi |first1=Brian |title=A tsunami of bankruptcies are about to wash away America's retail sector |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/a-tsunami-of-bankruptcies-are-about-to-wash-away-americas-retail-sector-142047677.html |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> is the closing of numerous [[economy of North America|North American]] [[brick-and-mortar]] [[retail]] stores, especially those of large chains, starting around 2010 and continuing onward.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.businessinsider.com/store-closures-in-2018-will-eclipse-2017-2018-1 |title=A tsunami of store closings is about to hit the US \u2014 and it's expected to eclipse the retail carnage of 2017 |last=Peterson |first=Hayley |date=January 1, 2018 |website= businessinsider.com |access-date= January 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"atlantic\" /> \nIn 2019, US retailers announced 9,302 store closings, a 59% jump from 2018, and the highest number since tracking the data began in 2012.<ref name=\"closing 28\">[https://amp.cnn.com/cnn/2020/01/08/business/macys-store-closures/index.html Macy's is closing 28 stores and a Bloomingdale's store], Jordan Valinsky, [[CNN]] Business, January 8, 2020</ref>\nOver 12,000 physical stores have closed due to factors including over-expansion of malls, rising rents, bankruptcies of [[leveraged buyout]]s, low quarterly profits outside holiday binge spending, delayed effects of the [[Great Recession]],<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/04/retail-meltdown-of-2017/522384/|title=What in the World Is Causing the Retail Meltdown of 2017?|first=Derek|last=Thompson|date=April 10, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2017|magazine=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref> and changes in spending habits. North American consumers have shifted their purchasing habits due to various factors, including [[experience economy|experience-spending]] versus material goods and homes, casual fashion in relaxed [[dress code]]s, as well as the rise of [[e-commerce]],<ref>[https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/companies/these-haunting-photos-of-the-retail-apocalypse-reveal-a-new-normal-in-america/ss-BByFpjX Photo slideshow of shuttered retail stores and shopping centers] ''[[Business Insider]]''</ref> mostly in the form of competition from juggernaut companies such as {{anchor|Amazon effect}}[[Amazon.com]] and [[Walmart]]. A further late 2017 ''[[Business Insider]]'' report by Kate Taylor dubbed this phenomenon the \"Amazon effect,\" and calculated that [[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]] was generating greater than 50% of the growth of retail sales.<ref name=\"business-insider-amazon-effect-1nov2017\">{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=One statistic shows how much Amazon could dominate the future of retail |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/retail-apocalypse-amazon-accounts-for-half-of-all-retail-growth-2017-11 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |publisher=[[Business Insider]] |date=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2020, the rash of bankruptcies and store closings is expected to greatly intensify due to the [[Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], with most retail stores closed (other than those selling food or hardware) and no reopening date set in most U.S. states. Existing apparel stock will have to be sold at deep discounts at reopening. [[Yahoo! Finance]] referred to a \"retail tsunami\" about to happen, with [[Neiman Marcus]] set to file for bankruptcy and the future of [[J.C. Penney]] in particular, in question. <ref name=yahoo/>\n\nThe most productive retailers in the US during the retail apocalypse are the discount superstores [[Walmart]] and [[Target Corporation|Target]], the low-cost \"[[fast-fashion]]\" brands (e.g., [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]], [[Uniqlo]], [[Cotton On]], and [[H&M]]), off-price department stores ([[Ross Stores]] and DD's Discounts, [[Marshalls]] and [[Burlington (department store)|Burlington]]) and [[dollar stores]] (e.g., [[Dollar General]] and [[Dollar Tree]]).<ref>[https://qz.com/1120552/the-retail-apocalypse-isnt-just-amazon-its-that-the-middle-class-is-disappearing/ The US middle class is disappearing, which makes dollar stores very happy] Helen Edwards & Dave Edwards, [[Qz.com]] 8 December 2017</ref>\nAt least one [[private equity firm]], [[Sycamore Partners]], has made money buying assets from brick-and-mortar chains during the retail apocalypse.<ref name=\"Made a Fortune\">{{cite news\n| last= Gottfried\n| first= Miriam \n| url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-one-investor-made-a-fortune-picking-over-the-retail-apocalypse-1521643491\n| title= How One Investor Made a Fortune Picking Over the Retail Apocalypse\n| newspaper= [[Wall Street Journal]] \n| date= March 21, 2018\n}}</ref> [[Pop-up retail]], including seasonal retailers such as [[Spirit Halloween]], operating temporarily in vacant spots after companies go out of business have become more common during the retail apocalypse.\n\nResearch from IHL Group finds that when a retailer closes a lot of stores, it says more about the individual retailer rather than the retail industry overall. In 2019, the 20 stores announcing the most closures [[Pareto principle|represent]] 75% of all closures. IHL found that for each retailer that is closing stores in 2019 more than 5 retail chains are opening stores, which is up from the 3.7 ratio in 2018. IHL also reported that the number of chains adding stores in 2019 has increased 56%, while the number of closing stores has decreased by 66% in the last year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chainstoreage.com/real-estate/ihl-study-five-retailers-opening-stores-for-every-retailer-closing-stores|title=IHL Study: Five retailers opening stores for every retailer closing stores|website=Chain Store Age|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref \n[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-13/retail-apocalypse-gives-more-women-a-shot-as-ceo Retail Apocalypse Gives More Women a Shot as CEO: A strong bench of female candidates is benefiting from the industry\u2019s woes] [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]], Jordyn Holman and Jeff Green, December 13, 2019</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe term \"retail apocalypse\" began gaining widespread usage in 2017 following multiple announcements from many major retailers of plans to either discontinue or greatly scale back a retail presence, including companies such as [[H.H. Gregg]], [[Family Christian Stores]] and [[The Limited]] all going out of business entirely.<ref name=\"whioohioimpact\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.whio.com/business/retail-apocalypse-500-stores-more-close-this-year/RzTeZhnIk13YIlF0skFV3H|title=RETAIL APOCALYPSE: 3,500 stores or more to close this year|last=Driscoll|first=Kara|date=March 27, 2017|work=WHIO TV 7|accessdate=April 8, 2017|publisher=[[WHIO-TV]]}}</ref> ''[[The Atlantic]]'' described the phenomenon as \"The Great Retail Apocalypse of 2017,\" reporting nine retail bankruptcies and several apparel companies having their stock hit new lows, including that of [[Lululemon]], [[Urban Outfitters]], [[American Eagle Outfitters|American Eagle]].<ref name=\"atlantic\" /> [[Credit Suisse]], a major global financial services company, predicted that 25% of U.S. malls remaining in 2017 could close by 2022.<ref name=\"gymboree\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/06/12/childrens-apparel-chain-gymboree-files-chapter-11-bankruptcy/102772792/|title=Gymboree files bankruptcy, closing up to 450 stores|first=Nathan|last=Bomey|date=June 12, 2017|accessdate=June 12, 2017|newspaper=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n\nSince at least 2010, various economic factors have resulted in the closing of many North American stores, particularly in the [[department store]] industry. For example, [[Sears Holdings]] had more than 3,500 stores and 355,000 employees in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/12/timeline-the-rise-and-fall-of-sears.html|title=Timeline: The rise and fall of Sears|last=Schoen|first=Lauren Thomas, Dawn Kopecki, John W.|date=2018-10-12|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> By the end of 2016, Sears operated 1,430 stores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/15/sears-files-for-bankruptcy.html|title=Sears files for bankruptcy, and Eddie Lampert steps down as CEO|last=Thomas|first=Lauren Hirsch,Lauren|date=2018-10-15|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> In October 2018, Sears filed for bankruptcy and announced they would close an additional 142 of their 687 stores.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2018/10/15/sears-bankruptcy/1595399002/|title=Sears files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, to close 142 more stores|last=Jones|first=Charisse|last2=Bomey|first2=Nathan|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> At the time of filing, Sears had 68,000 employees.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe retail apocalypse has had a [[domino effect]] on suppliers; [[Hasbro]], for example, cited the loss of the [[Toys \"R\" Us]] chain as a major cause for lost revenue and layoffs the company imposed in October 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wivb.com/news/national/hasbro-points-to-toys-r-us-demise-in-announcing-layoffs/1542038375|title=Hasbro points to Toys R Us' demise in announcing layoffs|publisher=CBS News|date=October 22, 2018|accessdate=October 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2020, the rash of bankruptcies and store closings is expected to greatly intensify due to the [[Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], with [[Yahoo! Finance]] referring to a \"retail tsunami\" about to happen.<ref name=yahoo/>\n\n==Factors==\n{{Quote box\n| title = \n| quote = ... several trends\u2014including the rise of [[e-commerce]], the over-supply of malls, and the surprising effects of a restaurant renaissance\u2014have conspired to change the face of American shopping.\n| source = ''[[The Atlantic]]''<ref name=\"atlantic\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 30em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 85%\n| title_bg = \n| title_fnt = \n| salign = right\n}}\nThe main factor cited in the closing of retail stores in the retail apocalypse is the shift in consumer habits towards online shopping.<ref>Mark James, [https://target-help.com/retail-apocalypse/ Retail Apocalypse Online competition drives store closings] ''[https://target-help.com/retail-apocalypse/]'', July 16, 2018</ref> Holiday sales for e-commerce were reported as increasing by 11% for 2016 compared with 2015 by Adobe Digital Insights, with Slice Intelligence reporting an even more generous 20% increase. Comparatively, brick-and-mortar stores saw an overall increase of only 1.6%, with physical department stores experiencing a 4.8% decline.<ref name=\"practicale\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.practicalecommerce.com/articles/132707-2016-Holiday-Ecommerce-Wrap-up|title=2016 Holiday Ecommerce Wrap-up|first=Marcia|last=Kaplan|date=January 12, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2017|publisher=PracticalEcommerce}}</ref>\n\nAnother factor is an over-supply of [[shopping mall|malls]],<ref>Marc Bain, [https://qz.com/1032723/theres-much-more-empty-retail-space-in-the-us-than-in-other-countries-on-a-per-capita-level/ America\u2019s vast swaths of retail space have become a burden in the age of e-commerce] [[qz.com]] July 19, 2017</ref> as the growth rate of malls between 1970 and 2015 was over twice the growth rate of the population. In 2004, [[Malcolm Gladwell]] wrote that investment in malls was artificially accelerated when the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] introduced [[accelerated depreciation]] into the tax code in 1954.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gladwell |first=Malcolm |date=March 15, 2004 |title=The Terrazzo Jungle |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2004/03/15/the-terrazzo-jungle |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=November 9, 2017 }}</ref> Despite the construction of new malls, mall visits declined by 50% between 2010\u20132013 with further declines reported in each successive year.<ref>Josh Sanburn, [http://time.com/4865957/death-and-life-shopping-mall/ Why the Death of Malls Is About More Than Shopping] ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'', July 20, 2017</ref> A third major reported factor is the \"restaurant renaissance,\" a shift in consumer spending habits for their disposable cash from material purchases such as clothing towards [[restaurant|dining out]] and [[travel]].<ref name=\"atlantic\" />\n\nAnother cited factor is the \"[[Middle-class squeeze|death]] of the [[American middle class]],\" resulting in large-scale closures of retailers such as [[Macy's]] and [[Sears]], which traditionally relied on spending from this market segment.<ref name=\"middleclass\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/amazon-and-walmart-confirm-the-death-of-the-middle-class-2017-6|title=Amazon's and Walmart's latest moves confirm the death of the middle class as we know it|first=Hayley|last=Peterson|date=June 6, 2017|accessdate=June 6, 2017|website=[[Business Insider]]}}</ref> Particularly in rural areas, [[variety store]]s such as [[Dollar General]], once thought to be unaffected by the apocalypse since they have continued growing rapidly, are now perceived as being at best a symptom of the phenomenon, and at worst a direct cause of rural, independent retailers collapsing, unable to compete with the lower margins that national chains can sustain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/19/business/dollar-general-opposition/index.html|title=Dollar stores are facing backlash across America|last=Business|first=Nathaniel Meyersohn, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Misra |first=Tanvi |date=December 20, 2018 |title=The Dollar Store Backlash Has Begun |url=https://www.citylab.com/equity/2018/12/closest-grocery-store-to-me-dollar-store-food-desert-bargain/577777/ |work=[[CityLab (web magazine)|CityLab]] |accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe final factor in poor brick-and-mortar sales performance is a combination of poor retail management coupled with an overcritical eye towards quarterly dividends: a lack of accurate inventory control creates both underperforming and out-of-stock merchandise, causing a poor shopping experience for customers in order to optimize short-term balance sheets,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paularosenblum/2014/04/15/walmarts-out-of-stock-problem-only-half-the-story/#1fb788873696|title=Walmart's Out Of Stock Problem: Only Half The Story?|last=Rosenblum|first=Paula|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref> the latter of which also influences the desire to understaff retail stores in order to keep claimed profits high.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsrresearch.com/research/the-walmart-out-of-stock-problem-lessons-learned|title=The Walmart Out-of-Stock Problem: Lessons Learned|website=www.rsrresearch.com|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref> Furthermore, many long-standing chain retailers are overloaded with debt, often from [[leveraged buyout]]s from [[private equity]] firms, which hinders the profitable operation of retail chains.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/147669/real-retail-killer|title=The Real Retail Killer|work=The New Republic|access-date=2018-11-27|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/brick-and-mortar-retail-private-equity-debt-financing-lbo-2017-8?international=true&r=US&IR=T|title=The retail apocalypse is being fueled by private equity firms adding to debt loads|work=Business Insider|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref>\n\n==Affected retailers==\n{{main|List of retailers affected by the retail apocalypse}}\n[[Sears Holdings]] filed for bankruptcy protection in October 2018 and planned to close about 142 of its 700 stores.\n\n[[Borders Books]] closed all stores and [[Chapter 7, Title 11, United States Code|filed for bankruptcy]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ovide|first=Shira|title=Bookstore Chain Borders Is Dead|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/deals/2011/07/18/its-almost-official-borders-is-dead|accessdate=July 28, 2011|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=July 18, 2011}}</ref> Rival bookseller [[Barnes & Noble]] acquired Borders' trademarks and customer list.\n[[File:Babies \"R\" Us - Manchester, Connecticut.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Toys \"R\" Us]] closed all its US stores in June 2018]]\n[[Toys \"R\" Us]] filed for bankruptcy<ref>[https://finance.yahoo.com/news/toys-r-us-just-beginning-retail-defaults-2018-182915327.html Toys \"R\" Us Just The Beginning of Retail Defaults in 2018] Krystal Hu, [[Yahoo! Finance]], March 15, 2018</ref> and closed all its US stores in June 2018.<ref>Brad Tuttle, [http://time.com/money/4931640/toys-r-us-sales-bankruptcy-debt/ Up Next in the Retail Apocalypse: Toys R Us?] [[Time.com]] September 7, 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/29/toys-r-us-closing-sales-stores-retail-toys.html Toys R Us closing its stores] Darren Geeter, [[CNBC]], 29 June 2018</ref>\n\n[[Bloomingdale's]] in 2012 announced it would close four stores, including at the [[Mall of America]] in [[Bloomington, Minnesota]]. Additionally, a home store at [[Oakbrook Center]] in [[Oak Brook, Illinois]] and full-line stores in [[Perimeter Mall]] in [[Dunwoody, Georgia]] and at [[White Flint Mall]] in [[North Bethesda, Maryland]] have closed their doors. On January 3, 2013, Bloomingdale's announced that they would close the [[Las Vegas]] Home store at [[Fashion Show Mall]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Zackie Binkes |url=http://www.vegasinc.com/news/2013/jan/03/bloomingdales-closing-store-fashion-show-mall/ |title=Bloomingdale's store closing at Fashion Show mall |publisher=Vegas Inc |date= 2013-01-03|accessdate=February 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Guess (clothing)|GUESS?]] closed 60 stores in 2017 and was expected to close more than 100 stores in 2018,<ref name=\"life support\" /> leaving roughly half of its high of 400 stores.<ref name=\"life support\">[https://www.forbes.com/sites/pamdanziger/2018/01/14/9-fashion-retailers-on-life-support/ 9 fashion retailers on life support] Pamela N. Danziger, [[Forbes.com]] 2018/01/14</ref>\n\n[[J. C. Penney]] announced in February 2017 that it would close 138 stores in 2017. Liquidation sales began on May 22, and stores closed by July 31.<ref name=\"penneydelay\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.whio.com/business/penney-postponing-store-closures/s7JjaCX6utJWzrJeZwAbFP/|title=JC Penney postponing store closures|first=Kara|last=Driscoll|date=April 13, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2017|publisher=WHIO-TV}}</ref> Another 8 stores and a distribution center closed in 2018. J. C. Penney announced plans to close a total of 30 stores in 2019.<ref>[https://amp.usatoday.com/amp/3013368002 J.C. Penney to close 24 more stores: Sales fall as department stores struggle] NATHAN BOMEY, ''[[USA TODAY]]'', 28 February 2019</ref>\n\n[[J. Crew]] closed 61 stores in 2017 and closed additional stores in the first quarter of 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lehighvalleylive.com/lehigh-county/index.ssf/2018/03/j_crew_ann_taylor_out_at_lehig.html |title=J. Crew, Ann Taylor out at Lehigh Valley Mall |last=Cassi |first=Sarah |date=March 15, 2018 |website=lehighvalleylive.com |access-date=March 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Payless ShoeSource]] plans to close all its 2,000 stores in the US and Canada,<ref>[https://www.today.com/today/amp/tdna148992 Payless ShoeSource plans to liquidate and close all U.S. stores] ''TODAY'', Ronnie Koenig, February 16, 2019</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4975274/payless-shoesource-stores-closing-canada/|title=Payless to close all 248 Canadian stores, liquidation sales expected {{!}} Globalnews.ca|date=2019-02-19|website=globalnews.ca|language=en|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref> and is going out of business.\n\n[[Topshop]] is closing all its US stores as its parent company, [[Arcadia Group]], seeks to restructure after filing for bankruptcy.<ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/24/business/topshop-topman-store-closing/index.html Topshop is closing all US stores] [[CNN]], Nathaniel Meyersohn, May 24, 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.afr.com/business/retail/clothing-and-accessories/topshop-pulls-out-of-the-us-australian-stores-in-doubt-20190603-p51u36 Topshop pulls out of the US, last Australian store in doubt] ''[[Australian Financial Review]]'', Sue Mitchell, June 4, 2019</ref>\n\n[[Barneys New York]] plans to close 15 stores after filing for [[Chapter 11 bankruptcy]]. <ref>[https://wwd.com/business-news/financial/barneys-new-york-richard-perry-bankruptcy-1203225430/ Barneys Files for Chapter 11 Bankruptcy Protection: The luxe department store has been struggling with higher rent and a changing consumer] ''[[Women's Wear Daily]]'', Evan Clark and Sindhu Sundar, August 6, 2019</ref><ref>[https://amp.usatoday.com/amp/1930050001 Barneys New York files for bankruptcy and announces 15 closing stores] KELLY TYKO, [[USA TODAY]], 6 August 2019</ref>Authentic Brands Group acquired the chain and licensed it to [[Saks Fifth Avenue]], and close the last seven stores. \n\n[[Forever 21]] filed for bankruptcy in October 2019 and said it would close up to 178 in the US and 350 stores globally.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/forever-21-bankruptcy-when-to-spend-gift-cards-2019-10 Forever 21 has filed for bankruptcy] ''[[Business Insider]]'', Shoshy Ciment, October 3, 2019\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/29/business/forever-21-bankruptcy/index.html|title=Forever 21 files for bankruptcy, intends to close up to 178 of its US stores.|last=Business|first=Nathaniel Meyersohn and Chris Isidore, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n[[A.C. Moore]] announced in November 2019 that all 145 locations will be closed.<ref>[https://nypost.com/2019/11/26/ac-moore-going-out-of-business-will-close-all-145-stores/ A C Moore going out of business] ''New York Post'', 2019/11/26</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Macy's]] announced it would close 125 department stores over the next three years,<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/04/macys-to-close-125-stores-sees-480-million-in-restructuring-costs-to-2000-corporate-jobs.html Macy\u2019s to close 125 stores, cut 2,000 corporate jobs, in hunt for growth] [[CNBC]], Lauren Thomas, February 4, 2020 </ref> following a sales decline of 3.9% at stores open for at least a year, which Macy's CEO Jeff Gennette said was \"steeper than we expected.\"<ref name=\"closing 28\" />\n[[File:Macy's\u00ae Hilldale - panoramio.jpg|right|thumb|300px| [[Macy's]] announced it would close 125 department stores 2020-2023]]\n\n[[Express, Inc.]] announced 31 store closures in January 2020; and 35 more stores will close by the end of January 2021. All other Express stores will close by 2022.<ref>[https://amp.usatoday.com/amp/4567461002 Express is closing 31 stores] KELLY TYKO, [[USA TODAY]], 23 January 2020</ref>\n\n[[Pier 1 Imports]] filed [[Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] proceedings in the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in February 2020.<ref>[https://www.newsy.com/stories/pier-1-imports-files-for-bankruptcy-protections/ Pier 1 Imports Files For Chapter 11 Protections] Briana Koeneman, ''newsy'', February 17, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 5, 2020, [[Art Van|Art Van Furniture]] announced that it would be closing all of its company-owned stores as it plans to file for [[chapter 11 bankruptcy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/money/business/2020/03/05/art-van-furniture-bankruptcy-liquidation/4951107002/|title=Art Van Furniture to close its stores, begin liquidation sales|last=Reindl|first=JC|date=2020-03-05|website=Detroit Free Press|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/05/art-van-store-closings-art-van-furniture-bankruptcy-liquidation/4962599002/?utm_source=feedblitz&utm_medium=FeedBlitzRss&utm_campaign=usatodaycommoney-topstories USA Today]</ref>\n\nOn April 19, 2020, [[Neiman Marcus]], announced it would file for bankruptcy as early as that week.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/19/business/19reuters-neimanmarcus-bankruptcy-exclusive.html]</ref>\n\n==Retailers succeeding in the apocalypse==\n[[File:Ulta Beauty Ann Arbor.JPG|thumb|right|[[Ulta Beauty]] opened 100 stores in 2018.]]\n[[File:Build-A-BearWorkshopVaughanMills.JPG|thumb|As of 2018, [[Build-A-Bear Workshop]] had expanded its physical footprint by 12% and had been profitable for four straight years.<ref>{{cite news| last= Bahler | first= Kristen| url= http://time.com/money/5216826/toys-r-us-retail-closing/| title= As Toys R' Us Closes, Only One Major Toy Store Is Thriving in the Retail Apocalypse| magazine= [[Time (magazine)|Time]]| date= March 27, 2018| accessdate=}}</ref>]]\nIn the second half of 2017 and throughout 2018, the media and analyst community began recognizing retail as an industry in transition, rather than demise. [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] said in May 2018 that 'the death of retail has been greatly exaggerated' and Telsey Advisory Group stated that 'retail is not dead' in August 2018 following news that the SPDR S&P Retail ETF had risen 13% year to date to a record high, more than double the return of the S&P 500 Index.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/31/digital-retailers-and-foreign-brands-fill-empty-us-malls.html|title=Is the retail collapse over? Shopping mall owners think so.|last=Thomas|first=Lauren|date=2018-07-31|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-05-01/e-commerce-costs-rise-just-as-commercial-real-estate-costs-fall|title=The Return of the Brick-and-Mortar Store|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, SeekingAlpha reported that 90% of purchases were still made in physical stores.<ref name=\"Wake Up\" /> SeekingAlpha noted that the top ten retailers ([[Walmart]], [[Kroger]], [[Costco]], [[Home Depot]], [[CVS Health|CVS]], [[Walgreens]], [[Amazon.com]], [[Target Corporation|Target]], [[Lowe's]] and [[Albertsons]]) are mostly brick-and-mortar operations.<ref name=\"Wake Up\">{{Cite news|url=https://seekingalpha.com/article/4184162-retail-apocalypse-wake-experience-renaissance?page=3|title=What Retail Apocalypse? Wake Up And Experience The 'Renaissance'|last=Thomas|first=Brad|date=2018-06-27|work=Seeking Alpha|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nNumerous online retailers including [[Warby Parker]], [[Untuckit]], [[Casper Sleep]], [[Away (luggage)|Away]], [[Wayfair]] and [[The RealReal]] have announced plans to open their first physical stores and expand their existing footprints in 2018 and beyond.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/31/digital-retailers-and-foreign-brands-fill-empty-us-malls.html|title=Is the retail collapse over? Shopping mall owners think so.|last=Thomas|first=Lauren|date=2018-07-31|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/casper-a-web-pioneer-to-open-200-stores-1533729600|title=Casper, a Web Pioneer, to Open 200 Stores|last=Safdar|first=Khadeeja|work=WSJ|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40575801/as-luggage-startups-drop-like-flies-away-beefs-up-with-249-jobs|title=As luggage startups drop like flies, Away beefs up with 249 jobs|date=2018-05-21|work=Fast Company|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n[[JLL (company)|JLL]] reports that digitally native brands will open 850 stores in the next five years. These retailers are finding that opening a physical store has a halo effect on web traffic: A study from the International Council of Shopping Centers shows that a new store increases traffic to that retailer's website by an average of 37% and drives up share of web traffic within that market by 27%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.retaildive.com/news/e-commerce-pure-plays-set-to-open-850-stores-in-five-years/539320/|title=Digitally native brands set to open 850 stores in 5 years|work=Retail Dive|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reports.icsc.org/thehaloeffect|title=The Halo Effect: How Bricks Impact Clicks|website=reports.icsc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-10-22/warby-parker-and-casper-are-coming-to-a-strip-mall-near-you|title=Warby Parker and Casper Are Coming to a Strip Mall Near You|website=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2014 to 2020, [[beauty supply store]] [[Ulta Beauty]] approximately doubled its number of stores, from 675 in 2014 to 1,254 retail stores across 50 states as of February 1, 2020.<ref>ir.ultabeauty.com/overview/default.aspx</ref>\n\nParticularly in rural areas, dollar stores ([[variety store]]s) such as [[Dollar General]], [[Dollar Tree]] and [[Family Dollar]] have continued growing rapidly.<ref name=dollar/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Business|History|Companies|United States}}\n*[[Dead mall]]\n*[[Economic history of the United States]]\n*[[Experience economy]]\n*[[Pop-up shop]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n; Videos:\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BBmvMpZCNJg|title=American shopping malls struggle to survive|work=[[CBS Sunday Morning]]|publisher=[[CBS]]|date=2014-03-30}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I7y1FoFqtiw|title=The rise and fall of the American shopping mall|work=[[PBS Newshour]]|publisher=[[PBS]]|date=2014-11-28}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oooVC3zfDc8|title=What America's shopping mall decline means for social space|publisher=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|date=2018-04-06}}\n\n==External links==\n*Brian Sozzi, [https://www.thestreet.com/story/14298940/1/coach-ceo-perfectly-explains-what-must-be-done-to-survive-retail-apocalypse.html Coach CEO Perfectly Explains What Must Be Done to Survive Retail Apocalypse] [[thestreet.com]] September 8, 2017\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/13/fashion/shopping-online-retail.html The Death Knell for the Bricks-and-Mortar Store? Not Yet] MATTHEW SCHNEIER, [[New York Times]], November 13, 2017\n*[http://www.newser.com/story/253582/the-mall-was-dead-except-for-the-jc-penney.html What It's Like to Work in the Last Big Store in a Dying Mall] [[Washington Post]]/Newser, Kate Seamons, January 2, 2018\n\n{{Economic history}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:2013 in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2018 in Canada]]\n[[Category:2016 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2017 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2018 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Economic history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Urban decay]]\n[[Category:Economic problems]]\n[[Category:2016 in economics]]\n[[Category:2017 in economics]]\n[[Category:2018 in economics]]\n[[Category:2019 in economics]]\n[[Category:History of retail in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Featous", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFactors:lkcorporate debt bubble", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retail_apocalypse"}
